<HEADLINE> Russian Orphans Turned Artists Tour  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a well known clown-doctor in tow, four
17-year-old Russian orphans turned artists will start an American
tour Monday in a Senate office building.
</P>
<P>
   They are ''Maria's Children,'' a training group founded seven
years ago by Maria Yeliseyeva, 35, to give more meaning to the life
of children in Russian orphanages. She is an artist who lives in a
suburban Moscow apartment with her computer-programmer husband.
They have four children of their own and two orphans they have
adopted, and there are usually other orphans around.
</P>
<P>
   ''When everybody's gone to bed, there's no more floor space
left,'' Dr. Patch Evans told a news conference. He met Yeliseyeva
on a tour of hospitals in Russia, one of many he has made around
the world, treating patients free of charge and often appearing in
the clown suit he wore Friday.
</P>
<P>
   His unconventional life was the subject of a 1998 Hollywood
film, ''Patch Adams,'' starring Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Janna Novikova, Inna Agaltsova, Sveta Khokhlova and Sasha Demin
sat in a row at the National Press Club with a 6-by-8-foot tapestry
across their knees. They hope to sell it for as much as $4,000.
They also have 150 pictures priced at $150 to $2,000 -- highly
colored and tightly packed views of the Kremlin, onion-domed
churches and other Russian scenes.
</P>
<P>
   They want to raise money to train more of the 650,000 children
in Russian orphanages, many of them classified as weak-minded.
Their American sponsors call them systematically misdiagnosed --
essentially bright, eager children whose education has been
neglected.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings will be put on show first in the Russell Senate
Office Building on Monday through Friday, and then for another two
weeks at Washington's Russian Cultural Center, which will hold an
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Other auctions are due to be held in New York, where the
paintings will be seen at the National Arts Club July 23-Aug. 6; at
the Edina Southdale Court in Minneapolis, Aug. 11-19 and at the
Bumbershoot Festival in Seattle, Sept. 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the web at: http://www.mariaschildren.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
