<HEADLINE> FBI Steps Into E-Mail Case  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- FBI computer technicians are stepping into the
case of the missing White House e-mails, trying to recover
thousands of lost messages that presidential aides say they are
unable to pull from computer backup tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest twist in the controversy over the e-mails played out
Friday in the courtroom of U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth, who
is presiding over a civil case involving the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth authorized the White House to turn over some tapes to
the Justice Department campaign finance task force and Independent
Counsel Robert Ray to see if the FBI can carry out the task the
White House has failed at for the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would like to give a date certain'' on producing the
e-mails, but ''unfortunately we're not in a position to do so,''
Justice Department attorney Elizabeth Shapiro told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not waiting another year'' to get the e-mail, Lamberth
replied. ''They are talking'' in the White House ''about another
year to get to the end'' of copying the tapes and recovering the
e-mails, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Independent Counsel and the Justice Department
''came to us and said the FBI might have a faster way to do this,''
said White House spokesman Jake Siewert. ''The FBI is going to take
a look and see if they can recover some of the e-mail from the
tapes. We finalized an agreement earlier this week to do that.
They'll take a test batch and look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Siewert said the e-mail recovery process is complicated because
outside contractors hired by the White House are ''building the
software'' to recapture the messages and ''this is not software
that is commercially available. We're literally having to create
the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as May 3, presidential aides said they would be able
to search and produce e-mails as early as June and would be able to
continue to do so on a rolling basis throughout the summer and
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very disappointed that the White House has not been
able to move forward with greater dispatch,'' said Jim Wilson,
chief investigator for the House Government Reform Committee.
''Given these new developments, at a very minimum, they should have
kept Congress informed of the fact that they were making no
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear the Clinton-Gore White House is attempting to
delay the e-mail production until after the election,'' said Larry
Klayman, head of the conservative legal group Judicial Watch that
brought the lawsuit against the Clinton administration that
prompted Friday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said computer contractors hired by the White House are
concerned that machines used to copy the backup tapes aren't up to
the task of round-the-clock use.
</P>
<P>
   If the machines broke while a backup tape was being copied, some
data would be lost and then ''people would be saying lots of
things, I'm sure,'' Shapiro told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The White House disclosed belatedly earlier this year that
thousands of e-mails, including some from Vice President Al Gore's
office, were not properly archived because of a computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the messages were never reviewed by White House
lawyers to determine if they should have been turned over under
subpoena to investigations ranging from impeachment and Whitewater
to campaign fund raising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 0113 </TRAILER>
