<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Democracy Questioned  </HEADLINE>
By KEN GUGGENHEIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Sunday's presidential race is considered the
fairest, most competitive in modern Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Mexico to be considered a true democracy, the opposition
says, governing party candidate Francisco Labastida has to do more
than run an honest race: He has to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The argument goes like this: If Labastida wins, he'll extend his
Institutional Revolutionary Party's hold on the presidency to 77
years. And 77 years of single-party rule is inherently
undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   It raises an intriguing question: Can a country be considered
democratic when the same party governs for 77 years?
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, the governing party, known as the PRI, says the
answer is yes. If the election is fair and Labastida is the top
vote-getter, that's what democracy is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ''A democracy exists now in modern times where there are the
conditions and there is a real possibility'' for a change of
government, said Javier Trevino, a senior adviser to the Labastida
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility exists now. Labastida's main rival, Vicente
Fox, is so close to Labastida in opinion polls that the race is
considered a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   But to Fox, a possibility isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''For Mexico to be considered a democracy, there has to be a
change in power,'' Fox told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the issue perplexing is that the PRI's situation is
unique. No other party now in power anywhere in the world has
governed as long. The only real comparison for longevity are the 71
years the Communist Party ruled the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, the PRI dominated all aspects of
Mexican politics, keeping the ruling class in power and preserving
social stability. Its identity was synonymous with the nation's --
its colors are the national colors -- and it won most elections in
landslides, often relying on patronage and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But the country has become more democratic in the past 12 years
and opposition candidates have made major gains, capturing
governorships, important mayoral seats and ending the PRI's
majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has had to change to stay competitive. In November, it
held its first presidential primary. It was a race lauded by the
PRI as evidence that the party had become truly democratic -- and
disparaged by the opposition as rigged to ensure the victory of
Labastida, seen as the favorite of President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Perspectives about how democratic Mexico's political system is
depend on how the PRI is viewed: Is it now just another party --
albeit the biggest -- in Mexico's political process? Or does it
continue to hold an unfair advantage?
</P>
<P>
   Trevino, the Labastida adviser, said the greatest proof that
Mexico is already democratic is that half the population lives
under opposition state or local governments. And the presidential
race has been fair, he said. Media coverage and campaign financing
have been mostly balanced and the process is overseen by a
respected, independent electoral institute.
</P>
<P>
   To some scholars, there's something odd about insisting that a
party lose a race to prove it's democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't make a test of democratic governance whether one
particular party wins a given election,'' said Abraham Lowenthal,
president of the Pacific Council on International Policy in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He said the real test of Mexico's democratic credentials will be
issues such as whether the PRI continues to become more democratic,
how the new Congress works with the new president, and whether
Mexican news media becomes a more effective watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   Yet others argue that Mexico's case is exceptional -- that the
PRI has been such a dominant force that Mexicans won't believe the
country has changed until it loses the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have my doubts that in the minds of people that you can
convince them that this is a democracy if the same party keeps on
winning,'' said Yemile Mizrahi, a researcher at the Center of
Economic Investigation and Instruction in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   For congressman Carlos Heredia, foreign policy spokesman for the
leftist Democratic Revolution Party, even a Labastida loss wouldn't
prove that Mexico has evolved into a democracy. He said there are
too many flaws in the political process, including electoral crimes
that go unpunished and PRI officials using federal funds for
political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   A PRI loss of the presidency, he said ''is a necessary but
insufficient condition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 0139 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zedillo Paves Way For Opposition  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- During his recent forays through the Mexican
republic, outgoing President Ernesto Zedillo has repeated it like a
mantra: Sunday's presidential elections will be fair and
fraud-free.
</P>
<P>
   For Zedillo, the statement is as much a personal wish as it is a
public reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   If he can persuade the public to accept what is likely to be a
narrow victory for either of the main candidates on July 2, he will
help seal an image as the leader who ushered in some of the most
dramatic economic and political reforms in Mexico's history.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's still got one big bump in the road, and that is to manage
the outcome of this election,'' whether the winner is ruling-party
candidate Francisco Labastida or opposition challenger Vicente Fox,
said George Grayson, a Mexico expert at the College of William and
Mary in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got to be able to negotiate and bargain and compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, a Yale-educated technocrat with more of an interest in
economics than politics, was pulled reluctantly into his public
leadership role in 1994 when the ruling-party candidate, Luis
Donaldo Colosio, was assassinated months before the election.
</P>
<P>
   A president who never actually asked for the job, Zedillo was
perhaps less beholden than those before him to party ''dinosaurs''
opposed to significant changes in the political status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Other events also pushed Zedillo in the direction of reform,
according to Joseph L. Klesner, a Mexico expert with the
Washington-based Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   In the months preceding the 1994 elections, the North American
Free Trade Agreement was implemented, Zapatista rebels rose up in
Chiapas, another high-profile politician was murdered and Mexico
spun into economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tumult of 1994 ... seems to have set Zedillo on a plan to
promote Mexican democracy,'' Klesner wrote in a pre-election
report.
</P>
<P>
   During his six-year term, Zedillo has overseen a series of
democratic reforms, the most important of which was his decision to
abandon the long-standing practice of having the outgoing president
handpick his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Zedillo promoted a primary for the ruling-party
candidates -- a process that for the first time in the party's 71
years of uninterrupted rule saw its members openly debating,
criticizing and challenging each other.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo also oversaw reforms that allowed an opposition
candidate to win the Mexico City mayorship in 1997, as well as the
Federal Electoral Institute's transformation to complete autonomy
from the government. The institute is the agency responsible for
organizing and monitoring the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some of Zedillo's actions have been ''a la Mexicana,''
in Grayson's words: During the ruling-party primary, for example,
he actively promoted Labastida and went so far as to even forbid
other potential rivals from entering the contest.
</P>
<P>
   And he has used recent road trips not only to publicly champion
clean elections, but to carry out a morally debatable party
tradition: spending hundreds of millions of dollars on public
programs and projects to promote Labastida's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things change here slowly and gradually,'' Grayson said. ''And
they've certainly changed a lot more under Zedillo in both the
economic and the political spheres than they have under anyone else
in recent memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The daily highway dedications and construction groundbreakings
over which Zedillo has presided in recent weeks have served not
only to boost Labastida's candidacy, but to reassure party leaders
that he did his part to keep the party in power. Having completed
that duty, he will be freer and more likely to recognize a Fox
victory on election day, Grayson says.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Labastida wins, Zedillo will have the task
of calming Fox supporters who suspect fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it is a Fox victory that would cement Zedillo's
place in history as a democratic reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Labastida wins, then I think Zedillo still gets a good deal
of credit,'' Grayson says, ''but the chapter on him will be briefer
and perhaps further back in the history book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 0148 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't To Limit UC at Los Alamos Lab  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department, reacting to a series of
security lapses, says it will strip the University of California of
its security and some management responsibilities involving nuclear
weapons programs at two laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson told the university its
contracts for managing the Los Alamos lab in New Mexico and the
Lawrence Livermore facility in California ''must be restructured
... to make much-needed improvements to security and other facility
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The university ''will still be actively involved'' in scientific
aspects of the nuclear weapons programs, but some other management
responsibilities, especially security, would be transferred
elsewhere, Richardson said in an interview Friday. He called the
university's security management unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring is expected to be worked out by September as
part of a renegotiation of the government's contract with the
university, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The university welcomes the opportunity to work with DOE in
this effort and to create a path forward that meets all security
needs,'' university President Richard Atkinson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said it was important to keep the university's
''strong science and academic expertise'' as part of the weapons
program ''so weapons scientists feel comfortable for their
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The university, which has managed the nuclear weapons program at
Los Alamos since 1943 and the Manhattan Project, which exploded
America's first nuclear device in the New Mexico desert, has come
under sharp criticism for security lapses in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The two-month disappearance of two computer hard drives from a
vault at Los Alamos caused a growing number of lawmakers in
Congress to question whether a university atmosphere can mix with
security needs of the nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's still a culture of lax security,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   The government contract with the University of California
expires in 2002. DOE officials said the contract is expected to be
re-negotiated this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The department will immediately begin negotiations with the
university to bring into their operations specific security and
management expertise to implement (security) improvements,'' a DOE
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The new chief of DOE's nuclear weapons agency, Undersecretary
John Gordon, was placed in charge of overseeing the contract
renegotiating and to address with the university ''the serious
shortcomings ... at our weapons laboratories,'' the department
said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was angered by the disappearance of the hard drives,
but even more incensed by not having learned of the security breach
for nearly a month after it became known to some Los Alamos
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the secretary also was highly critical of the
university's handling of a sophisticated laser program at the
Lawrence Livermore lab. After repeatedly assuring the $1 billion
laser program was on schedule and within budget, Richardson was
told without warning there would be a $300 million cost overrun and
substantial delays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 0204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 9, Giants 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Gary Sheffield hit two home runs and had
four RBIs, and Kevin Brown continued his mastery of the San
Francisco Giants as the Los Angeles Dodgers won 9-2 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sheffield's 19th career multihomer game, fourth this
season, as the Dodgers won for the third time in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (7-2) allowed two runs on six hits and a season-high five
walks in seven innings as he improved to 8-1 against the Giants in
10 career starts. He also struck out a season-low three.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley hit his 15th homer, becoming the first opponent to
hit a homer into McCovey's Cove, the body of water just outside
Pacific Bell Park. He also hit two doubles for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Russ Ortiz (4-8) allowed six runs on seven hits
and five walks in 3 2-3 innings. While the Giants have the best
home ERA in the majors, Ortiz is 0-4 with a 6.69 ERA at the new
bayfront ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kent drove in both of the Giants' runs to increase his
NL-leading total to 78 as San Francisco lost its third straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 2-0 lead in the first when Eric Karros hit a
sacrifice fly and Hundley doubled home a run.
</P>
<P>
   Kent drove in a run with a sacrifice fly in the first, then
later added a run-scoring single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield led off the third with his 26th homer of the season, a
shot that just cleared the left-field fence near the foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cora led off the fourth with a double, and Todd
Hollandsworth walked. With two outs, Sheffield hit the first pitch
from Ortiz into the left-field bleachers to make it 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had three consecutive hits in the third, but failed
to score as Shawn Green threw out Bill Mueller at third base trying
to take an extra base on a hit by Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek and Karros each drove in runs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Bullpen coach Rick Dempsey was the Dodgers' first-base
coach as John Shelby serves his three-game suspension, a result of
his involvement in the altercation at Wrigley Field on May 16. ...
Giants RHP Mark Gardner is scheduled to pitch one of the games of
the day-night doubleheader on July 4 against the Colorado Rockies.
... Dodgers SS Kevin Elster missed his third straight with a sore
left hamstring. ... Sheffield and Karros passed Bonds and Kent as
the NL's top RBI, 137-135.
</P>
</TEXT>
