<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Mexico Wary of Elections  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MIGUEL ELOXOCHITLAN, Mexico (AP) -- A group of Nahua Indians
came trudging barefoot down a dirt road to meet a senator about
alleged campaign abuses in the run-up to Sunday's presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator could not drive up to meet them -- the road ends
in a narrow mountain trail a short distance away, the result of a
project the Indians say was aborted when the villagers of Atexacapa
met and decided to abandon support for the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   National election officials say Sunday's presidential election
will be the fairest ever. That rings hollow, however, for many in
this underdeveloped corner of central Mexico, where challenging the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, the PRI, can carry a
heavy price.
</P>
<P>
   Eloxochitlan, in the Sierra Negra of Puebla state, is among
Mexico's poorest regions. Neither roads nor electricity have
reached the 260 people of Atexacapa, whose men work for about $1.50
a day as laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fernando Herrero of the National Action Party has come to
hear the Nahua's complaints of electoral intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Putting on a T-shirt for Vicente Fox is a big challenge for
them,'' he said, referring to the opposition presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers said they feared meeting Herrero inside of
Eloxochitlan, a PRI stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Concepcion Hernandez, the Federal Electoral Institute's
representative for the region, said she feared that independent
poll workers might feel threatened into withdrawing in favor of
people picked by local bosses.
</P>
<P>
   She said Mexico's widely praised electoral system works well,
''but ... did not contemplate the influence of the bosses in Indian
zones.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Margarito Hernandez, himself Nahua, denied allegations of
pressure in favor of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is freedom here for the parties,'' a smiling Hernandez
told reporters in his office while surrounded by about 30
villagers. ''We do not incline toward any and the law is
respected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Atexacapa, however, claim that soldiers carrying
lists they said were from the mayor have sought National Action
activists in the village on suspicion of drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ''They planted the (accusation of) crime,'' said Martin Barrios
of the independent Commission for the Defense of Human Rights in
Tehuacan, the nearest sizable city.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of soldiers have been in the region since the army
uncovered a training camp for Zapatista rebels nearby three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Barrios says local bosses have also formed private, armed
''white guards'' -- once a common practice in rural Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   State spokesmen deny that claim, but local officials do seem
well-protected.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Salvador, who allegedly introduced National Action to
Atexacapa, said he was jailed for two days for ''disobedience'' in
1996. He said he has kept a low profile since April when he
appeared on the lists soldiers brought to the village.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral institute's Hernandez said she found that the
PRI-dominated town council in Coxcatlan has set a 200 peso fine for
failing to vote for the PRI. In neighboring Tlacotepec de Diaz, she
said, opposition voters run the risk of being jailed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of opposition political parties who seek any
excuse to say there are violations of the law,'' insisted Victor
Manuel Serrano, adviser to the mayor of Tlacotepec de Diaz, who
belongs to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Isidrio de Jesus Martinez, 19, who had supported an opposition
mayoral candidate, said a local police chief shot him in the leg
late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said he was giving it to me because I did not help the
mayor in his campaign,'' Martinez, who no longer can walk, said
from another town where he is hiding from the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors have mounted a criminal investigation of the
police chief, however he remains on the job, according to
Martinez's attorney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 0206 </TRAILER>
