<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Presbyterians Vote Against Gay Ceremonies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- The chief policy-making body of the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.A.) voted by a narrow margin Friday to recommend barring ministers
from officiating at commitment ceremonies for gay couples. The measure still
must be ratified by ministers and elders nationwide before it can become part of
the Book of Order, the constitution for the 2.6 million-member denomination. It
passed the church's General Assembly with 17 votes to spare.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First Amendment Said Valued in U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Free speech is a great American principle that should be
protected -- except when it protects the airing of views people find offensive,
a majority in a new poll says. On press freedom, half said U.S. news media have
too much freedom, while the other half said the press has about the right amount
or not enough freedom, said the poll by the Freedom Forum's First Amendment
Center. About half in the new poll said art should not be put in public places
if it may offend some members of the community, and public speech that offends
members of a religious group should not be allowed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ark. Court Sues To Disbar Clinton
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton was sued Friday by an Arkansas
Supreme Court committee seeking to strip him of his law license. The committee's
lawsuit accused the president of engaging in serious misconduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair, including false testimony, that ''damages the legal
profession.'' The five-page lawsuit asks that Clinton be disbarred for
conducting ''himself in a manner that violates the model rules of professional
conduct as adopted by the Arkansas Supreme Court.'' The president has 30 days to
respond, and his private attorney vowed a vigorous fight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
8 Dead in Denmark Pearl Jam Concert
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- At least eight people were crushed to death and
three others were injured Friday when fans rushed the stage during a Pearl Jam
concert at one of Europe's largest rock festivals. Members of Pearl Jam had
urged the crowd to move back because people were being pressed up against the
stage, and the warning was repeated on loudspeakers, Danish radio said. The band
halted its performance and the following session by The Cure was canceled. But
concerts on six other stages went on, a festival spokesman said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Pulls Plug on Video Poker
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Fourteen years after video gambling became legal in
South Carolina and began growing into a $3 billion industry, the plug was pulled
on the machines as a statewide ban took effect Saturday. The end came only after
a late-night legal drama that reached the state Supreme Court. Video poker
became legal in South Carolina after a lawmaker slipped a provision into a bill
in 1986. Anti-gambling forces fought hard to outlaw the machines, a battle that
came to a head in 1998 when then-Gov. David Beasley, a Republican, called video
gambling ''a cancer on South Carolina'' and vowed to get rid of the industry.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Perot Shuns Bid for President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Two-time presidential candidate Ross Perot Friday turned down
backer' efforts to put his name on the Reform Party's primary ballot, removing a
potential hurdle for Pat Buchanan's bid. The Texas billionaire decided against
running in the primary because he had no intention of actually competing for the
White House in November, Russell Verney, Perot's spokesman, said. Verney said
Perot didn't want to put his name on the Reform ballot only to stop Buchanan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Can't Find E-Mails
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House has yet to recover any missing e-mails
sought by investigators, a judge disclosed Friday, but it is turning over backup
tapes that might contain the messages to Independent Counsel Robert Ray and the
Justice Department. Two law enforcement officials told The Associated Press that
the FBI will now step in and try to retrieve the missing e-mails.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 50; Nasdaq Climbs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rallying in the final hour of trading, the Dow Jones
industrial average Friday erased a small loss and finished up 49.85 at 10,447.89
in heavy trading. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by a narrow margin. The Nasdaq
composite index, lifted by computer chips and semiconducter stocks, rose 88.88
to 3,966.11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds 5, Diamondbacks 4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Pete Harnisch, just off the disabled list, got his first
victory of the season and drove in the go-ahead runs with a bases-loaded single
Friday night as the Cincinnati Reds beat the Arizona Diamondbacks 5-4. Harnisch,
in his first outing since May 5, gave up a two-run home run to Jay Bell, the
second batter he faced, but then shut out the Diamondbacks the next five innings
as the Reds improved to 7-0 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
