<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ark. Court Sues To Disbar Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES JEFFERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A state Supreme Court committee has
taken the unprecedented step of suing a sitting president to strip
him of his law license, accusing President Clinton of dishonesty
and deceit in a scathing lawsuit that declares him unfit to
practice law.
</P>
<P>
   The court-appointed Committee on Professional Conduct, which
hears complaints against lawyers licensed in the state, said Friday
that Clinton was not fit to practice law because -- under oath -- he
gave deceptive answers in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case
about his relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''The conduct of Mr. Clinton ... was motivated by a desire to
protect himself from the embarrassment of his own conduct,'' the
committee said in the five-page lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The president has 30 days to respond and it's unlikely the case
will be resolved before he leaves office in January. Clinton's
attorney said Friday that he would fight the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fundamentally disagree with the complaint,'' David Kendall
said in a statement released by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has said he would not get involved personally in
the case, claimed the committee was responding too harshly and that
there would be ''no way in the world'' that he could lose his
license. He arranged for an evening round of golf to begin the
Fourth of July holiday weekend shortly after receiving the news.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee used mild language in announcing the lawsuit
May 22, the document it filed with the Pulaski County Circuit Court
on Friday sharply denounced Clinton and said his actions had harmed
others in the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The panel accused the president of ''serious misconduct'' and
defined the term as ''involving dishonesty, deceit, fraud and
misrepresentation.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also said the president's conduct in the Jones case
''damages the legal profession and demonstrates a lack of overall
fitness to hold a license to practice law.''
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the lawsuit were dozens of pages of exhibits,
including a partial transcript of Clinton's deposition in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   The judge initially assigned to the case, John Ward, immediately
recused, and the court closed Friday before a replacement could be
named. Clinton had appointed Ward to a judgeship in 1989, and Ward
also was a Democratic state representative when Clinton was
Arkansas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Once a judge is named, the lawsuit will fall into the regular
mix of the court docket -- the state's busiest -- and any local
judge's decision would likely be appealed to the state Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The committee based its lawsuit on complaints filed by a federal
judge and by an Atlanta law firm, the Southeastern Legal
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it was simply a misunderstanding or a misstatement by the
president, where the information was false and it wasn't done with
intent, that's one thing. That would probably lead to a letter of
reprimand,'' said Matt Glavin, president of the Atlanta group.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge, Susan Webber Wright, found Clinton in
contempt April 12, 1999, for statements he made in the Jones case.
She was out of her office Friday and has not publicly commented on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a former Arkansas state worker, sued Clinton in 1994,
claiming he made a crude pass at her in a Little Rock hotel room
three years earlier. Jones lawyers' drew Lewinsky into the case in
an attempt to show a pattern of sexual misconduct by Clinton. The
trail was later picked up by independent counsel Kenneth Starr, and
it led to Clinton's impeachment by the House, though he was
acquitted at the subsequent Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Clinton said in his sworn deposition: ''I have
never had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, he told a federal grand jury that he had had an
inappropriate relationship with Lewinsky. He said the conduct he
engaged in with Lewinsky did not meet the definition of sex that
was given at the start of the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Wright found Clinton in contempt and fined him $90,000. Jones
settled out of court for $850,000, and Clinton did not have to
admit any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said that because Clinton did not contest the
contempt citation -- he paid the fine -- it had to proceed with a
harsh sanction. ''Mr. Clinton neither requested a hearing, nor did
he appeal the (contempt) order,'' the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a licensed lawyer since Sept. 7, 1973, was attorney
general of Arkansas from 1977 to 1979 and once taught at the
University of Arkansas law school. He has not practiced law since
the early 1980s, between his first and second terms as governor of
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time that an effort has been made to strip a
sitting president of his law license. New York pulled Richard
Nixon's license to practice law, but that came after he resigned
from the presidency Aug. 9, 1974, during the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern Legal Foundation: http://www.southeasternlegal.org
</P>
<P>
   The White House: http://www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
