<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By AFSHIN VALINEJAD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran (AP) - A senior judicial official said Saturday
that three of the 13 Jews tried on charges of spying for Israel had
been acquitted and 10 were sentenced to fines, lashes and
unspecified jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   Hossein Ali Amiri, the provincial judiciary chief of Fars
province where the monthlong trial has been held, gave no other
details in comments aired on state-run Tehran television.
</P>
<P>
   Amiri said two Muslim suspects also were acquitted, and two more
Muslims had received sentences similar to the other Jews.
</P>
<P>
   He did not specify the length of the jail terms for any of the
accused.
</P>
<P>
   The case has cast a pall over Iran's Jewish community and drawn
concerned attention from the United States, Israel and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has denied the accused were its agents and has been
joined by international human rights groups and other countries in
questioning whether the accused could be fairly tried in a process
in which there was no jury, in which the judge also acted as
prosecutor, and from which observers were banned.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about fairness increased when state television
broadcast confessions from two of the defendants. Defense lawyers
said they were not given a chance to consult with their clients
before their confessions, which came after months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the defendants had pleaded guilty, four had pleaded
innocent and one acknowledged passing information but maintained
his action did not constitute espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, two Jews were hanged at Tehran's Evin prison on similar
spying charges. Iranian officials have differed on whether the
death penalty could be applied in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Jewish community, although it has dwindled over the
decades, remains the Middle East's largest outside Israel. Iranian
Jews are allowed to practice aspects of their religion but are
forbidden to teach Hebrew, the liturgical language.
</P>
<P>
   At its height, Iran's Jewish community numbered about 100,000
and was still around 80,000 just before Iran's 1979 Islamic
revolution. Now there are about 25,000 Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Shiraz, home to 6,000 of Iran's Jews, was once the capital of
the Persian empire and attracted people of all faiths because of
its wealth and tolerance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 0239 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
