<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Still No Trace of Indonesia Ship  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANADO, Indonesia (AP) -- Since Senaen cried as she clutched her
2-year-old son, waiting with other distraught relatives Friday as
searchers turned up no trace of a ferryboat overloaded with
hundreds of refugees fleeing sectarian violence on the Maluku
islands.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband is missing. I can only pray that God will protect
him and the rest,'' Senaen said, standing with the others by a
ramshackle dock on Manado's waterfront. ''We left our home because
of the violence and the fighting. We came here to safety a few days
ago. He was to join us.''
</P>
<P>
   After two days of searching, an Indonesian patrol boat Saturday
sighted afloat what searchers believed was the ferry, said Cmdr.
Djoko Sudarman, head of the search and rescue operation. He
declined to give the exact location of the sighting or any details
about why searchers believed the boat was the wooden-hulled Cahaya
Bahari, which had been scheduled to reach Manado Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the 492 passengers and crew was not immediately
known.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to fly over the location and see for ourselves,''
said Sudarman. ''We hope that everyone on board is safe but I
cannot give you any further details until I see for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact with the ship was lost Thursday soon after its captain
radioed that it was taking on water in stormy seas about 1,440
miles northeast of Indonesia's capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no debris in the water, no bodies, no oil slick,
nothing,'' said navy Cmdr. Djoko Sumaryono, who is heading the
search effort. ''We hope there are survivors, but we have found no
one. So far it is a mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   The ferry disappeared while on a voyage of more than 200 miles
to Manado in Sulawesi from the Malukus, a corner of the Indonesian
archipelago where violence between Muslims and Christians has
killed almost 3,000 people of both faiths in the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's agent in Manado, Theddy David, said the
130-foot-long, 420-ton vessel was licensed to carry only 290
passengers, but was packed with nearly 500 passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
   He said many aboard the ferry were refugees from Duma, a
Christian village in the Malukus where more than 100 people were
killed in an attack by Muslim fighters June 19. Muslims make up
about 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people, but Christians
are in the majority in many parts of the Malukus, known as the
Moluccas or Spice Islands during Dutch colonial days.
</P>
<P>
   The weather improved Friday and a navy reconnaissance plane and
an air force helicopter searched along with three navy ships and
dozens of fishing craft and larger vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Sumaryono said then there was a slim chance that the ship might
be drifting outside the search area with survivors aboard, but said
it was ''very unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Other possible explanations are that the captain radioed in a
wrong position during his final distress call or perhaps debris
were washed out into the deep ocean by strong currents.
</P>
<P>
   On Manado's waterfront, hundreds waited anxiously for their
missing relatives, who embarked Wednesday on the ferry journey.
Some women sat in a crowded waiting room, fiddling with their
wedding rings. Other people sobbed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no news. We know nothing about what has happened,''
said Merlin Tuwangena, who was waiting for a group of 30 relatives
from Duma, among them small children, old people and some wounded
in the religious violence.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred yards away, hundreds of other people climbed on or
off three ferries, similar to the missing Cahaya Bahari. The
ferries' interiors were crammed with cargo and people lying on rows
of double-decker bunks surrounded by possessions in boxes and bags.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping disasters with large losses of life are common in this
country of some 17,000 islands. Poorly maintained vessels are often
overloaded by captains eager to maximize profits.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, three people drowned when a wooden cargo boat
illegally carrying 52 passengers capsized off the southeast coast
of Sulawesi in rough seas, said officials in the port city of
Kendari. The six crew told authorities the passengers forced them
to set sail to a nearby island despite bad weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 0250 </TRAILER>
