<HEADLINE> City settles lawsuit with former deputy police commissioner for $1 million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The city has agreed to pay $1 million to a
former deputy police commissioner who said she was fired after
refusing to revise a report critical of the handling of a sexual
harassment case.
</P>
<P>
   The city's agreement to pay was contained in a judgment entered
Friday in federal court in Manhattan on behalf of Sandra M. Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh, who headed the NYPD's Office of Equal Employment
Opportunity from 1988 until her dismissal last year, was awarded
the settlement less than two weeks before Police Commissioner
Howard Safir was scheduled for a court-ordered deposition.
</P>
<P>
   In the report that led to her ouster, Marsh ultimately ruled
that the underlying sexual-harassment charges against a lieutenant
were unfound. But she found that Assistant Chief Eugene Devlin, the
Staten Island borough commander, had illegally retaliated against a
female officer by transferring her after she filed a complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh also found that Devlin's deputy chief, Philip Erickson,
had lied to investigators, an offto the lawsuit, when Marsh presented the report
to
Safir and top police officials, she was asked by Deputy
Commissioner for Legal Affairs George A. Grasso whether she
''understood'' that the report implicated the conduct of men with
30-year careers.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, the suit alleged, First Deputy Commissioner
Patrick E. Kelleher informed her Safir was ''very unhappy'' with
her conclusions and ordered the case reinvestigated and her report
rewritten. When she refused, Marsh said, she was fired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
