<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Egypt May Restore Relations  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran and Egypt will soon restore full
diplomatic ties after more than 20 years of strain, an adviser to
Iran's culture minister said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Normalization of diplomatic ties between Iran and Egypt is
being accomplished and we should expect an official announcement
soon,'' Mohammad Sadeq Hosseini told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate confirmation from Egypt, which has long
wanted Iran to change the name of a Tehran street named after the
assassin of Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   Hosseini, who is also the secretary of the non-governmental
Iran-Egypt Friendship Society, said Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi and his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa ''settled the few
remaining misunderstandings'' during a meeting this week on the
sidelines of an Islamic conference in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Ties were severed after Egypt's 1979 peace treaty with Israel.
Relations deteriorated further when Egypt gave refuge to the ousted
Iranian shah, who was buried in Cairo in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Relations began to improve after Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami, a political moderate, took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''Iran and Egypt have made a wise decision to restore ties and
any delay in normalization would be detrimental to both
countries,'' Hosseini said.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak spoke by telephone
last month -- the first direct contact between leaders of the two
states since Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has urged Iran to rename a street that is named after
Khaled al-Islambouli, a Muslim militant army officer who
assassinated Sadat in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has objected to Egypt's dealings with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
