<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Giuliani begins hormone treatment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who was diagnosed with
prostate cancer in late April, is receiving hormone therapy at a
Manhattan hospital while trying to decide on a final treatment, the
Daily News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Citing unidentified sources familiar with Giuliani's medical
situation, the newspaper said the mayor was being treated with
Lupron - a medication that blocks the production of testosterone,
the male hormone that prostate cancer cells thrive on.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office refused to comment Saturday on the report.
Giuliani was scheduled to attend the Long Island funeral of NYPD
Inspector Anthony Falco, but his office stressed that the mayor
would not speak with reporters following the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   While Lupron and other hormone blockers are not a cure for
prostate cancer, they can buy time for patients who want to
evaluate different therapies. The blockers are sometimes used
before surgery or radiation to shrink the prostate and reduce
prostate specific antigen, or PSA, levels.
</P>
<P>
   The most common side effects of Lupron are hot flashes and
impotence. Injections of the drug, which are administered monthly
or quarterly, can hold the cancer at bay for years, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has repeatedly refused to answer most questions about
his health since dropping out of the Senate race against first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton on May 19. He has told reporters he will
inform the public of his decision on a cancer treatment only when
he feels comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second most common type of cancer found in American men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
