<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moynihan's upstate estate for sale as couple tries to simplify life </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, N.Y. (AP) - The rural homestead where U.S. Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan and his family lived for 36 years, where he
wrote 18 books in an 1854 schoolhouse, where Hillary Rodham Clinton
symbolically began her run to replace him, is on sale for $1.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pat's giving up the Senate and I'm giving up the farm,'' the
retiring Democratic senator's wife, Elizabeth Moynihan, told the
Associated Press in a telephone interview Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, 73, finishes his fourth and final six-year term at the
end of this year. He announced in 1998 that he would not run again.
''You're in your 70s and you don't want to press that too long, do
you?'' he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth also cited age in what she said was her quick decision
to sell the home known as Derrymore. ''Everyone I know who is over
70 like me is trying to simplify their life,'' she said. She is two
months away from 71. Her three children are in their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have arthritis in the knees and I can't garden six hours a
day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was much more than gardening to care for the country
estate - comprised of two Greek Revival houses, two barns, the
schoolhouse, ponds, stream and 8,000 feet of road frontage on 500
acres.
</P>
<P>
   The Moynihans purchased the farm in February 1964, three months
after John F. Kennedy's assassination. As the senator tells it, his
wife traveled to Oneonta, found a real estate agent and committed
on the spot to the home in the hamlet of Pindar's Corners, about 57
miles west of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, this was the quiet sanctuary where one of the
Senate's leading intellects and a former Harvard professor wrote
and edited works on poverty, government and ''Counting Our
Blessings: Reflections on the Future of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The farm remained largely out of the political spotlight, though
it served as backdrop last July to a key moment in Clinton's
campaign. A couple hundred reporters with dozens of cameras
recorded Moynihan walking Clinton down the road from schoolhouse to
hayfield.
</P>
<P>
   But to Elizabeth, an architectural historian, Derrymore has been
more home than historic site, and she did not understand why most
would care about its sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing to me that it's a news story,'' she said. ''It's
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also has a condominium with what Elizabeth called ''a
wonderful view of Pennsylvania Avenue'' in Washington, D.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 1216 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Reject Multiparty Politics  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- In a referendum marked by low voter
turnout, Ugandans have overwhelmingly rejected multiparty politics
in favor of continuing with President Yoweri Museveni ''no-party''
system, according to provisional results announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With about 88 percent of the 16,500 polling stations in the East
African nation reporting, the Electoral Commission said 91 percent
of the votes cast in Thursday's referendum favored retaining the
National Resistance Movement as the country's political system as
opposed to returning to a multiparty system.
</P>
<P>
   Voter turnout was 44.9 percent of the 9.6 million registered
voters. The final, official results will be announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Western donors, who contributed $4.5 million to the cost of
holding the referendum, expressed concern Saturday that the results
could lead to a drift to a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The group of donors emphasizes the importance of insuring that
the movement system does not evolve into a de facto one-party
state. Experience shows that such development would not be in the
interest of transparent and accountable government in Uganda,''
their statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am happy that there has been collaboration among all groups
and people during the elections,'' said commission chairman Aziz
Kasujja. ''The votes which have so far not been received are from
areas like the north where people voted late because of problems
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In one county in northern Uganda, where rebels are active, only
11 percent of registered voters participated. Advocates of
multiparty politics could claim that as a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional political parties, allowed to exist in name only,
had called for a boycott of the vote. But it wasn't clear whether
the boycott, rainy weather or simply a lack of interest was
responsible for the low turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Political parties, which cannot campaign, raise funds or field
candidates on party colors, have argued that basic political rights
should never have been restricted when Museveni came to power in
1986 after a five-year guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   Museveni blames political parties for creating the religious and
ethnic divisions that plunged Uganda into chaos from the mid-1970s
until he assumed power. He was elected president in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 1240 </TRAILER>
