<DOCNO> APW20000701.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans Vote With Uncertainty  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAUCALPAN, Mexico (AP) -- When Leopoldo Becerril was young, he
rode his horse through this farm village of sweeping vistas, and
opposition political parties were as welcome as ''a dog in somebody
else's neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Becerril is 58 and Naucalpan is a chaotic suburb of
860,000 people governed by the opposition National Action Party --
an example of the dramatic changes that have given Mexico's
opposition a real shot at power in the presidential election
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   National Action's Vicente Fox is running roughly even in the
polls with Francisco Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the PRI, which hasn't lost a presidential race since it was
created as a party of power in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   For perhaps the first time in a century, and perhaps the first
time ever, Mexicans are voting with a great uncertainty about who
their next president will be.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even 10 or 15 years ago in Naucalpan, to go out campaigning in
some neighborhoods was to risk your hide,'' said Becerril, a
National Action activist. ''We left running as the stones flew.''
</P>
<P>
   On a national level, National Action's Luis H. Alvarez recalled
that when he ran for president in 1958, he was arrested and ''spent
several hours in jail as a criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   When he asked what the charge was, the jailer replied: ''being a
candidate of the opposition,'' Alvarez recalled in an interview
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''As for access to (broadcasting on) the radio, I could not have
even a single minute in the whole campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, like other major candidates, has received more than $100
million in government campaign financing and has run an intensive
television and radio campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in places such as Naucalpan that started in the 1950s
helped produce those changes, even as the PRI remains dominant in
the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   As Mexicans increasingly moved to cities and grew more educated,
the PRI's influence weakened. People began to demand political
reforms. Today, only about a quarter of Mexicans live in small
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   Naucalpan, a scattering of 16 farm towns with fewer than 100,000
people in 1960, exploded with suburbanites fleeing neighboring
Mexico City and farmers fleeing the impoverished, overcrowded
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Becerril, whose family has raised rodeo horses for generations,
saw the wide-open countryside become covered with factories,
low-income apartment blocks, luxury homes and a helter-skelter
scattering of commercial developments.
</P>
<P>
   Becerril's great-grandfather, grandfather and an uncle were PRI
mayors of Naucalpan. He joined National Action about 15 years ago --
not long after the new city's wealthy neighborhoods produced one of
the country's first directly elected opposition congressmen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the federal government for the first time recognized an
opposition party victory in a state. Baja California went to
National Action, known as the PAN.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of electoral reforms between 1989 and 1996,
opposition parties now govern about a dozen states and at least
eight of Mexico's 10 largest cities. Naucalpan, No. 11 on the list,
elected the PAN in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is now part of the ''blue corridor,'' a chain of suburban and
industrial cities west and north of Mexico City governed by the
PAN, whose colors are blue and white. Mexico City itself is
governed by the left-center Democratic Revolution Party.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, which once won elections with 80 to 90 percent of the
claimed vote, is struggling to surpass 42 percent this year against
the five other candidates on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 years ago Mexicans awoke the day following an election
uncertain of whom they had elected, the ruling party's Carlos
Salinas or maverick leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas was declared the winner after officials ''crashed'' the
vote-reporting computer when initial returns showed Cardenas ahead.
Millions of Mexicans -- including many analysts who studied the
election -- still believe Cardenas won.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas is a candidate again this year. But he finished third
in the generally clean 1994 election won by the PRI's Ernesto
Zedillo and is again in third place in the polls this year.
</P>
<P>
   While his party may take votes from Labastida in the
countryside, most analysts think he hurts Fox more by splitting the
vote of millions of Mexicans whose chief priority is to oust the
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a sign of progress that Cardenas says some things are
more important than defeating the PRI. Electing Fox, he said
recently, ''would mean a step backwards'' because of the PAN's
conservative social ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dire threat to the PRI this year, the party actually
could stage a comeback. In 1997, amid an economic slump, the party
lost its majority in Congress for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show it running near the level it would need to regain
that majority in the 500-seat lower house. It is expected to hold a
reduced majority in the 128-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The party also has hopes in Naucalpan, where PRI activists blame
their 1996 mayoral defeat on the bad economy and over-confidence.
They accuse National Action of ignoring poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PAN did not beat us in 1996,'' said PRI city councilman
Federico Delhumeau. ''It was simply that our people did not vote
for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
