<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: S. Leone Peacekeepers Attacked  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Gunmen fired on U.N. peacekeepers
at a checkpoint in Sierra Leone on Saturday, one day after a
Jordanian soldier was killed in a rebel ambush, U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordanian peacekeepers were staffing a checkpoint at Rokel
town, 15 miles east of the capital, Freetown, when they were
attacked by unidentified assailants. U.N. spokeswoman Hirut
Befecadu said there were casualties, but could provide no further
details.
</P>
<P>
   The attack came the day after Sierra Leonean rebels ambushed
another unit of Jordanian peacekeepers on their way from the
western town of Masiaka to join a convoy of U.N. vehicles at the
nearby town of Mile 91. One Jordanian soldier was killed and four
others were injured in the assault, which occurred 80 miles east of
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers returned fire. When they later searched the
house from which the gunfire had come, they found 11 bodies which
were identified as rebel fighters, Befecadu said.
</P>
<P>
   Revolutionary United Front rebels killed tens of thousands of
civilians and systematically maimed many more during the West
African country's eight-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgents signed a peace accord last July, but reignited
the conflict in early May when they seized 500 U.N. hostages and
began advancing toward Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages have since been released, and a ragtag alliance of
pro-government forces has been pushing the rebels away from the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 peacekeepers and observers remain surrounded,
however, at a U.N. compound in the rebel stronghold of Kailahun,
200 miles east of Freetown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
