<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boxing promoters in IBF scandal could lose licenses  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Revelations in the racketeering trial of IBF
founder Robert W. Lee have boxing officials in key venues
considering whether to banish some of the sport's biggest
promoters.
</P>
<P>
   No action is contemplated before the end of the racketeering
trial, which began here in April and could last several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the testimony of promoters such as Bob Arum and Cedric
Kushner, each involving $100,000 payoffs, is already under scrutiny
by officials in New Jersey and Nevada - the most lucrative states
for boxing because of their casinos - as well as California, which
has the most boxing matches of any state, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Don King, the most powerful promoter, is not expected to
testify. He could face scrutiny by licensing authorities because
federal prosecutors identify him as an unindicted coconspirator,
supported by testimony that he was the prime beneficiary of Lee's
manipulations of the IBF rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The other big promoter in the case, Main Events Inc. of Totowa,
N.J., believes it will escape discipline because it jettisoned
president Dino Duva, who testified he funneled $25,000 to Lee so
the IBF would follow its rules and rank one of his fighters as the
junior middleweight top contender in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter, Fernando Vargas, became the IBF champion and still
holds the 154-pound title.
</P>
<P>
   No promoters are on trial. They are licensed on a state-by-state
basis, where regulations generally say unsavory activity linked to
boxing can be grounds for punishment, including revocation of a
license.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm certainly monitoring,'' said Marc Ratner, executive
director of the Nevada Athletic Commission. ''We are getting our
transcripts, and observing from afar.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's chief legal counsel, Kirk Hendrick, said all
four of the big promoters hold Nevada licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are privileged licenses in the state of Nevada, and it
is certainly possible that disciplinary action could be taken,''
said Hendrick, a chief deputy state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada law allows discipline if a promoter ''conducted himself
at any time or place in a manner which is deemed by the commission
to reflect discredit to unarmed combat,'' Hendrick related.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal courtroom in Newark daily is an investigator with
the New Jersey Division of Gaming Enforcement, the agency that
examines promoters and other businesses because they need licenses
to work at casinos. It serves as the investigative arm of the New
Jersey Athletic Commission, which also licenses promoters.
</P>
<P>
   DGE director John Peter Suarez, a former federal prosecutor, has
said that promoters who may be involved with commercial bribery
''are a significant concern to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The four big promoters hold licenses to do business with New
Jersey casinos, which are subject to revocation if they cannot meet
the standards of ''good character, honesty and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Applying those standards, New Jersey in 1994 banned Don King
from doing business with Atlantic City casinos after he was
indicted on charges he bilked Lloyd's of London for training
expenses involving a 1991 fight that was canceled. The Casino
Control Commission vacated its order in 1998 after King was
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Any action directly related to boxing that discredits the sport
could lead to revocation of a promoter's license in California,
said Rob Lynch, executive officer of the state's boxing commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're conducting our own investigation, and we're following
right along with what happens in New Jersey,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   While California has the most cards, the biggest money is made
from fights in casinos, said Nigel Collins, editor of The Ring
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ''If both Nevada and New Jersey stop Kushner and Arum from
promoting in the casinos, it would be huge blow to those
promoters,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way boxing works today, the casinos in Atlantic City and
Nevada pay huge site fees to the promoters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos don't make money on ticket sales. Instead, ''They
bring in high-rollers from around the world for the fights, knowing
they are going to drop a lot of money,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties against a promoter could leave marquee fighters
looking for a new home. King's stable includes Evander Holyfield,
while Arum has Oscar De La Hoya, Kushner has Shane Mosley, and
Lennox Lewis fights for Main Events.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and other IBF officials are accused of taking $338,000 in a
span of more than a decade in exchange for favors and rigged
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters testifying against Lee, including Arum of Top Rank
Inc. of Las Vegas, and Kushner of Cedric Kushner Productions of New
York, have said payoffs were required to do business with the East
Orange, N.J.-based IBF.
</P>
<P>
   As one of three major sanctioning bodies for boxing in the
world, its rankings and decisions play a large role in the purses
earned by boxers, of which managers and promoters get a cut.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the alleged bribes stems from machinations in April
1995 regarding then-heavyweight champion George Foreman and Axel
Schulz, a German fighter. Foreman promoter Arum testified early
this month that he used a middleman to get $100,000 to the IBF to
sanction the Foreman-Schulz title fight. An exception was needed
because Schulz was unranked.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman won in a disputed split decision.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz promoter Kushner testified last week that he funneled
$100,000 to the IBF from his co-promoter, German businessman
Wilfrid Sauerland, for the organization to mandate a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   The IBF ordered the rematch, but Foreman relinquished its belt
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner also said he made cash payoffs to the IBF three to four
times a year from 1987 through 1994, in amounts ranging from $2,500
to $10,000, to ensure good treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures disturb Greg Sirb, executive director of the
Pennsylvania State Athletic Commission and president of the
Association of Boxing Commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm saddened,'' Sirb said. ''It hurts our sport. I think there
are a lot of young fighters who are looking at this and saying,
'This is why I didn't get ranked. This is why I didn't get a title
shot.' It hurts our image.''
</P>
<P>
   The four promoters are not licensed in Pennsylvania, but ''all
the states are looking at it, no question,'' Sirb said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
