<HEADLINE> Key Facts About Mexico Elections  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A look at Mexico's national elections:
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT STAKE: The six-year presidential term. All seats in Congress:
500 three-year terms in the Chamber of Deputies and 128 six-year
terms in the Senate. The mayoralty and other posts in Mexico City,
the capital. The governorships in Morelos and Guanajuato states.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE PARTIES: Ten parties have proposed six candidates for
president. The top three: the Institutional Revolutionary Party,
which has governed Mexico since 1929; the center-right National
Action Party and the center-left Democratic Revolution Party.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE ISSUES: Opposition parties say the ruling party must be
ousted to make Mexico fully democratic. The ruling party calls for
continuing the basic free-market economic course with more social
spending. It portrays opposition candidates as dangerous risks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTERS: Eligible are 58.7 million Mexicans. Millions who
live in the United States are effectively disenfranchised: they can
vote only in Mexico and there are fewer than 45,000 absentee
ballots they might be able to use in border districts.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTE: Polls open Sunday at 8 a.m. and close at 6 p.m. local
time. Because of time zone differences, the first polls will open
at 9 a.m. EDT and the last will close at 9 p.m. EDT. Each party can
assign workers to monitor each polling place. Poll workers are
chosen at random from the general population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 1312 </TRAILER>
