<HEADLINE> Look at Mexico Candidates  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The main candidates in Mexico's July 2 presidential
election:
FRANCISCO LABASTIDA:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Affiliation: Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has
governed Mexico for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 57. Born in Los Mochis in the Pacific state of Sinaloa.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Government analyst 1962-68; head of president's social
welfare department 1968-72; undersecretary of public investments
1972-75; director of fiscal promotion for Treasury Secretariat
1976-79; federal undersecretary of budgeting and planning 1979-82;
energy secretary 1982-86; governor of Sinaloa state, 1987-92;
ambassador to Portugal 1993-94; general director of federal bridges
and highways 1994-95, agriculture secretary 1995-98; interior
secretary 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   Education: Economics degree from National Autonomous University
of Mexico in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Married to Maria Teresa Uriarte, a historian. Four
children from a previous marriage. Another, illegitimate daughter
is a student at the University of Texas, El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Platform: Promises a crackdown on corruption, greater public
security, more resources for public education and more attention to
the poor. Has tried to soften the free-market message of his
party's last three presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Tennis, reading, movies.
</P>
<P>
   ----:
VICENTE FOX:
</P>
<P>
   Affiliation: Coalition of the center-right National Action
Party, of which he is a member, and the smaller Mexican Ecologist
Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 57. Born in Mexico City. Turns 58 on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Coca-Cola Inc. 1964-79, worked his way from delivery man
to president for Mexico and Central America; retired to form
farming and ranching business 1980-88; congressman 1980-88;
governor of Guanajuato state, 1995-present.
</P>
<P>
   Education: Studied business management at Iberoamerican
University in Mexico City; didn't finish degree but completed work
and received diploma during presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Separated. Four adopted children.
</P>
<P>
   Platform: Has campaigned mainly on toppling the ruling party and
ending corruption. Promises broad-based government and free-market
economy. Pledges to nearly double education spending. Wants Mexican
workers to be able to cross freely into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Reading, chess, horseback riding.
</P>
<P>
   ----:
CUAUHTEMOC CARDENAS:
</P>
<P>
   Affiliation: Coalition of five parties, including the Democratic
Revolution Party and the smaller Workers Party.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 66. Born in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Worked as a private engineer for two decades; senator
for three months in 1976; undersecretary at the agriculture
secretariat 1976-80; governor of western Michoacan state 1980-86;
left ruling party in 1987 and formed the Democratic Revolution
Party; ran for president in 1988 in fraud-tainted election; ran and
lost again in 1994; first elected mayor of Mexico City 1997-99.
</P>
<P>
   Education: Degree in civil engineering from Mexico's National
Autonomous University. Postgraduate studies in electrical
engineering and hydraulics in France.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Son of a former president, Cardenas lived in
presidential residence from infancy to age 6. Married to Maria
Celeste Batel. Three children.
</P>
<P>
   Platform: Favors larger state role and greater rights for Mexico
under trade treaties. Backs more investment in education. Wants new
constitution to increase power of legislature and guarantee right
to housing and work.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Family, movies, dominos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
