<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Writer Disappears in Jamaica  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEGRIL, Jamaica (AP) -- Stuck in Jamaica for longer than planned,
travel writer Claudia Kirschhoch decided to make the best of this
laid-back Caribbean resort. The 29-year-old American mixed with
locals, went to a reggae concert, sunbathed on the spectacular
white sands of Seven Mile Beach, read a book on Asian metaphysics.
</P>
<P>
   And then she disappeared -- leaving clothes, passport and wallet
behind.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, her anguished parents and authorities seem at a
loss to explain what happened. In a reflection of how the
investigation is going, police took the advice of a psychic this
week and searched caves along Negril's seaside cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculate Kirschhoch is in hiding. Others guess she
drowned. And many fear foul play -- a prospect that could bode ill
for a poor Caribbean country that is desperately dependent on the
tourist dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Already the $1 billion industry, which accounts for a tenth of
Jamaica's gross national product, is flat. The country is fighting
a reputation for gangland violence and for exposing visitors to its
aggressive brand of street vendor, the notoriously irksome
''higgler.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials note that the 1.2 million visitors who come here each
year -- equal to almost half the population -- almost always leave
unharmed. But they fear the high-profile nature of this case.
</P>
<P>
   ''If she's been hurt it would certainly not be helpful,'' said
hotel magnate Gordon ''Butch'' Stewart, whose Sandals chain invited
Kirschhoch to the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The missing woman's parents, Fred and Mary Ann Kirschhoch of
Morristown, N.J., have come here twice -- most recently this week,
with an ABC-TV crew in tow. They have offered a reward of $25,000,
held news conferences and walked around town, telling all who would
listen about their daughter and sometimes pulling out a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   This much is known: Kirschhoch arrived in Montego Bay on May 24
as part of a Sandals-sponsored tour for travel writers which was to
continue to Cuba. But when the Cuba leg was canceled because of
visa problems and all flights back to New York were booked, she
opted to stay at a Sandals resort in Negril, where she arrived May
25.
</P>
<P>
   That night she left the resort compound to see a reggae concert
''because she said she wanted to know Jamaica,'' said Tania
Grossinger, a New York City journalist who met Kirschhoch on the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast on May 27, Kirschhoch told Grossinger she might
go to Kingston to find reggae albums not sold in the United States.
She was last seen in the hotel lobby later that morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sandals executives said that when she didn't check out on June
1, they extended her stay. The next day they searched her room. The
only items believed missing were a bathing suit, sunglasses and a
small radio. Her passport, wallet, camera and house keys were
there.
</P>
<P>
   A team from the FBI quietly arrived last week and is keeping
mum. Kirschhoch's parents, meanwhile, say they feel she is alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something terrible has happened to her,'' said Mrs.
Kirschhoch, her voice brittle. ''I don't know what, but I know she
needs us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kirschhoch, a partner in an architectural firm, said his
daughter loved to travel, taking frequent trips to Italy and the
Canary Islands off West Africa -- ''her favorite spot on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Negril, it would seem, was an ideal venue for the curious young
woman to explore. For more than 30 years American and European
visitors have been drawn to the west coast town -- which, unlike the
crime-ridden capital, Kingston, was considered as safe as its
beaches were beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Police have received close to 400 calls from helpful citizens
claiming to have spotted Kirschhoch. And many police officers
thought they had done so as well: Stories of officers approaching
white women in towns around Jamaica abound.
</P>
<P>
   Peace Corps volunteer Angie Steely said she was apprehended by
officers near Kingston. As they stopped her, she said, they were
shouting: ''Look! Look! She the missing one!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
