<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researcher finds crows intriguing and perplexing  </HEADLINE>
By MARY ESCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) - Kevin McGowan knows crows aren't the most
popular of birds.
</P>
<P>
   They're noisy. They devour baby robins. They pluck corn
seedlings. You can't take a road trip without seeing one teasing
the intestines from a flattened rabbit. And they sometimes roost by
the tens of thousands, whitewashing cars as they rise in a
clamorous cloud at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, the somber black birds have been associated
with death -- both metaphorically, as dark omens, and literally, as
carrion eaters. Their macabre image was magnified last summer when
hundreds of crow corpses heralded the outbreak of mosquito-borne
West Nile virus in the New York City region.
</P>
<P>
   To McGowan, however, crows are intriguing, intelligent birds
with a complex social structure. And he ought to know. He has spent
the last 12 years tagging crows, following them around, and
recording every detail of their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   He has found that crows are smarter and more complicated than we
had imagined. And there is still much to learn, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just don't know an awful lot about these common birds,''
McGowan said in an interview. ''They're the least-studied game
animal in America. You start looking in the literature and you find
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, McGowan climbs pine trees to pull baby crows from
bushel basket-size nests of sticks, while furious parents swoop and
curse. He attaches numbered tags to their wings and color-coded
bands to their legs, so he can identify them and record their
behavior over the years.
</P>
<P>
   He has tagged more than 850 crows to date, and has kept close
track of about 75. Among his findings:
</P>
<P>
   -Crows mate for life and are cooperative breeders, with as many
as 15 birds from several generations staying with parents or
siblings to help raise young.
</P>
<P>
   -A crow doesn't breed until it's 2 to 6 years old, and should
live 17 to 21 years if it survives its first year (about half die
before they're a year old).
</P>
<P>
   -Breeders stay on their territory year-round, leaving only to
forage and roost, while non-breeders travel around more.
</P>
<P>
   -Crows have one brood a year and spend nearly four months
raising young, compared to songbirds such as robins which can have
four or five broods in a season.
</P>
<P>
   -The number of crows nesting and roosting in urban areas has
grown significantly in the past 30 years, although the overall crow
population has risen only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan got interested in crows while working on his doctoral
dissertation on the social behavior of Florida scrub jays in 1987.
He received a federal grant to study crows in 1988 after he came to
Ithaca, where his main job is curator of the Cornell University
Museum of Vertebrates.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a green Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology baseball cap
over his sandy hair, McGowan kept up a commentary on the life and
times of various local crows as he cruised the residential
neighborhoods of Ithaca on a recent spring day.
</P>
<P>
   His words frequently trailed off as he braked his mauve Subaru
and raised binoculars to his wire-rimmed glasses to read a wing
tag.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's ZP93,'' he said, focusing on the wing tag of a crow in
a tree behind a mobile home. ''He fledged out of this pine seven
years ago. He's still hanging around helping his parents.''
</P>
<P>
   As he made the rounds of various nests, McGowan occasionally
reached into a sack of peanuts behind his car seat and tossed a
handful to a cluster of crows eyeing him from the roadside.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try to get on their good side,'' McGowan said. Some follow
him in hopes of handouts, but others just shriek at him. ''They
hate me for climbing to their nests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the enduring mysteries about crows is, why do they hang
around for years to help parents or siblings raise young?
</P>
<P>
   This cooperative breeding behavior apparently did not evolve
through natural selection in crows, McGowan said, because it
doesn't seem to give them any competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some birds, it's obvious that there is a benefit to having
extra family members helping out,'' McGowan said. ''In some species
of tropical wrens, if you don't have at least four individuals in
your family you produce zero young because predation is so high.
But in crows, there doesn't seem to be any effect.''
</P>
<P>
   McGowan thought the benefit of having extra feeding help might
show up only in bad years. In 1995, he had the opportunity to test
that theory during a drought, which made earthworms scarce.
</P>
<P>
   He was excited to find that nests with helpers did produce more
young. But a closer look at the data showed the increased survival
rate was in the egg stage, having nothing to do with feeding help.
</P>
<P>
   ''So I still don't understand what's going on,'' McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan knows a lot of people don't share his enthusiasm for
crows.
</P>
<P>
   ''A constant comment I hear is, crows eat baby birds, so we
should get rid of them,'' McGowan said. ''The fact is, the birds
they're eating are adapted to heavy depredation. When we see a crow
with a baby robin, we assume that's one less robin in the world.
But if the crow didn't eat it, it would have died in migration, or
a hawk would have gotten it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crows invoke perhaps the greatest human wrath when they
congregate in huge numbers to roost. Last summer, a National
Geographic television show featured a roost of 50,000 crows in
Auburn. The city has been perplexed about what to do about the
noisy, messy birds.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan's advice: Leave them alone. Efforts to oust them will
probably just make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Auburn roost originally was near the state prison, McGowan
said. ''After the crows would settle down for the night, the guards
would flash their searchlights over them and they'd fly up and
defecate all over the cars in the prison parking lot,'' he said.
''Now, they're all over downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest smudge on the reputation of crows is their
association with West Nile Virus, which killed seven people and
sickened 62 others last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rare mosquito-borne disease was identified, wildlife
scientists were perplexed by the discovery of hundreds of dead
crows around the region. The deaths were later linked to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Are crows likely to spread this new disease?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, McGowan said. For one thing, crows generally don't
move far from their home territory. And the virus appears to be
more lethal to crows than other species. It's more likely to be
carried by other birds and animals that are infected but don't die,
McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Crows are the biggest victim of this disease,'' McGowan said.
''Because so many are killed by it, they can act as sentinels if it
does spread.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   McGowan's Web site:
http://cumv.bio.cornell.edu/mcgowan/crowinfo.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
