<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jailed man says prosecutors botched rape investigation  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Sitting in a prison cell for a rape he
claims never happened, Jerome Sweezy is beyond bitter. He is
consumed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have nothing left to lose,'' Sweezy says. ''The only thing
that drives me is the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth, prosecutors counter, is why the 45-year-old former
used car salesman was convicted of rape in 1994 and is now serving
a 3-to-9-year sentence at the Livingston Correctional Facility, a
medium-security prison 60 miles south of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters, however, say Sweezy has spent five years in
prison because of a lazy, bumbling investigation by Broome County
prosecutors, who failed to locate a number of witnesses who have
since cast more-than-reasonable doubt on the victim's story.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prosecutors have an obligation to seek justice not just
convictions,'' said James Weeks, director of the Office of Clinical
Programs at the Syracuse University College of Law, which has filed
papers to reopen Sweezy's case and is awaiting a judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sweezy says his ordinary life turned into a nightmare on June
15, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sweezy, a 20-year-old woman and an elderly man came
to Sweezy's dealership that day looking to sell the man's car.
After settling on a consignment deal, the pair left. Afterward,
Sweezy realized they had not left the car keys. Sweezy arranged to
meet the woman and ended up taking her for a ride. The woman began
flirting with Sweezy, who was married and had two young children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was kind of cute, I guess. Here I am, 36 at the
time, and here's this 20-year-old girl making a pass at me,'' said
Sweezy, who worked at IBM Corp. for 14 years before going into
business for himself.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Sweezy said he realizes now he was asking for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Once they reached the secluded road, the woman coaxed him to
pull over. She unzipped his pants and offered him oral sex in
gratitude for Sweezy's help in selling the car, Sweezy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said thanks, but no thanks. I took her back and dropped her
off, and that was it,'' said Sweezy, who refused to plea bargain
his case.
</P>
<P>
   That's his story. The woman had a different one.
</P>
<P>
   She told police she feared for her life. At trial in April 1994,
the woman added that Sweezy grabbed her neck during the encounter
and left red welts on her neck. The welts were not mentioned in her
initial statement to police, nor did any witnesses recall seeing
them.
</P>
<P>
   After Sweezy dropped her off, the woman said she fled to Robert
Mineah's house, the elderly man she said she cared for. Mineah
later told investigators that he had sex with the woman and often
let her use his credit card. Mineah was watching her two children.
She went to police the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The woman told jurors she was met at the door by Mineah and her
children. She said she picked up her daughter and clutched her
closely, relieved to have escaped her ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses who were later found by a private
investigator, the woman was anything but distraught.
</P>
<P>
   They said played cards and joked with her companions. Her only
reference to the man who had supposedly just assaulted her was to
tell them that he was ''a little weird'' but she thought she could
get a good deal from him on her car, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess anybody who doesn't want free sex is a little weird,''
Sweezy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweezy lost an appeal. In 1996, he asked for a new trial based
on the witnesses found by the private investigator and was
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   None of those witnesses, except Mineah, testified at his trial
because Assistant District Attorney Mary Ann Lehmann, now a city
judge, never bothered to locate them, even though she should have
known of their existence, Sweezy said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors never allowed defense attorney Thomas Saitta to
interview the victim despite repeated requests, according to
Saitta. The victim has since moved and prosecutors declined to
reveal her whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   In the motion to reopen his case, Sweezy alleged prosecutorial
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents show the woman told Lehmann several times during
a grand jury hearing Nov. 12, 1993 that other adults were present
when she returned to Mineah's house that day, Weeks said. Lehmann
failed to conduct a follow-up investigation or alert Sweezy's
defense attorney other potential witnesses existed, Weeks charged.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, court papers accused Lehmann of committing perjury
at the December 1996 appeals hearing when she testified that the
first time she ever heard of other adults at Mineah's house was in
May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lehmann and District Attorney Gerald Mollen refused to discuss
the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response opposing a new trial, Mollen said nothing
had changed since the 1996 hearing and there was ''still absolutely
no evidence'' to support the defense's allegations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The trial defense lawyer knew during trial exactly what the
trial prosecutor knew,'' he said, dismissing the idea that there
was any sinister plot to wrongly convict Sweezy.
</P>
<P>
   It was private investigator Phil Gallagher who tracked down the
auctioneer, several of his employees and another friend, Lisa Gage,
who were at Mineah's house that June day in 1993. Gallagher said he
did not do anything extraordinary in finding them.
</P>
<P>
   At the appeals hearing in December 1996, Broome County Judge
Martin Smith labeled as ''totally credible'' the evidence gathered
by Gallagher and the testimony of all the witnesses. Smith also
agreed that certain of the victim's statements ''were incredible
and unworthy of belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Smith concluded that the jury would not have
decided the case any differently if it had access to the evidence
uncovered by Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, six jurors thought otherwise and submitted signed
affidavits saying so.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also refused to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Jay Dinga, a conservative Republican who has been
outspoken in his support of get-tough criminal laws, has been a
longtime supporter of Sweezy's, writing the governor, attorney
general and others over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about treating someone who's guilty softly. What
is at issue is that a person can be sent away to state prison ...
based on evidence that was circumstantial at best, and later proved
contrary to the facts,'' Dinga said.
</P>
<P>
   Others have rallied behind Sweezy, including attorney Jon Getz,
who represented Betty Tyson, a former prostitute who languished in
a New York prison for nearly 25 years before her 1973 murder
conviction was overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are enough questions and issues of innocence that it
rates having a court review, and perhaps another trial,'' said
Getz. ''If he's really guilty, a trial will determine it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sweezy is determined to hold fast. Although he has
been an exemplary inmate, he has been passed over twice for parole
because he refuses to complete a required sex rehabilitation
course. To participate in the required program, he says, would be
tantamount to confessing guilt.
</P>
<P>
   His once successful business career is gone. His wife has
divorced him. He has not seen his two children in years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know I could fight this better from the outside,'' Sweezy
said. ''But I refuse to be a victim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll only be a victim if I let them get away with this,'' he
said. ''Someday, somebody will see the truth ... I think we're
getting a lot closer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
