<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TA: Subway operator fails second cocaine test  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A second cocaine test has come back with a
second positive result for the operator of a subway that derailed
in Brooklyn, injuring 66 people, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The motorman behind the wheel when a B train went off the tracks
on June 20 had requested the second test after an earlier one found
traces of cocaine, said Deirdre Parker, a Transit Authority
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News identified the operator as David Murray, 51, but
Parker said the TA was not releasing his name.
</P>
<P>
   She said investigators were still trying to determine the cause
of the accident. Officials have said they are looking at problems
with a switching mechanism that failed as the train changed tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The southbound B train was leaving the DeKalb station when the
wheels of the third car skipped off the track, sending riders
flying as the brakes automatically engaged.
</P>
<P>
   The operator has been suspended and notified that the MTA will
seek his dismissal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
