<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nations Renew Anti-Poverty Push  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Five years after they pledged to improve the lot
of the world's poor, governments at a U.N. summit agreed Saturday
to throw their weight behind a renewed effort to combat global
poverty -- but offered few firm commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates at the U.N. General Assembly's special session
reaffirmed promises made at 1995's first poverty summit in
Copenhagen, which since then have largely been ignored. They said
they are ''determined to give new momentum to our collective
efforts to improve the human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Their final statement stressed the importance of debt relief,
market access and more aid for developing countries. It said it
will cost $8 billion per year to achieve education for all, and
that new funding commitments are ''essential.'' But the statement
commits nations to nothing specific, and is not binding.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is hoping that it will nevertheless generate
the political will for prompt action.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1995 session the number of people in absolute poverty
-- living on less than a dollar a day -- has climbed about 200
million to 1.2 billion, the United Nations estimates. It now aims
to halve that figure by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, pressure groups and activists at the
Geneva summit said they were ''gravely concerned'' by that
deadline, which they said ''sentences hundreds of millions of
people, especially women, to continue living in abject conditions
for another generation.''
</P>
<P>
   They also were angered that no specific mention was made of the
so-called ''Tobin Tax'' -- a plan to raise money for development by
taxing currency transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Rich and poor at the meeting divided over the same arguments
that have hindered trade negotiations and other major conferences
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Developing countries complained that their products do not have
fair access to world markets and that creditors are not moving
quickly enough to write off crippling debt. But industrialized
nations said the poorer countries must begin to help themselves by
eliminating corruption, putting poverty reduction plans into place
and ensuring basic human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Copenhagen agreement called for developed countries to
donate at least 0.7 percent of their gross national product in
official development assistance, but only four nations -- Denmark,
Sweden, Norway and the Netherlands -- meet that target.
</P>
<P>
   The new declaration stresses the need to provide technological
assistance to poor countries. It calls for ''consideration ... of a
temporary debt standstill'' when countries are faced with a sudden
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Countries at the conference set a target of a 50 percent
improvement in adult literacy levels by 2015. By that same date,
they want to ensure the enrollment of all children in primary
school. They also agreed to ''further recognize the critical
importance of access to essential medicines at affordable prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We stand especially in the face of the worst enemy in the
world, namely HIV/AIDS,'' said Theo Ben Gurirab, president of the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva meeting was attended by 19 heads of state and
government, far short of the 117 who took part in the original
poverty summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people think it's a loss of time,'' conceded Roberto
Bissio of Social Watch, one of the interest groups that attended.
''But if we don't have a high-level political process, how do we
make the countries accountable for the few targets and objectives
that they commit themselves to implement?''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.un.org/socialsummit
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
