<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five misdiagnosed patients may have cancer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A least five women who allegedly received shoddy
mammograms from a pair of since-suspended Bronx doctors showed
possible signs of cancer when retested, state health officials
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The women were among an estimated 9,000 patients of Steven Bier
and Mario DiBlasio, two doctors who participated in a state program
to provide free cancer screening for uninsured and underinsured
women.
</P>
<P>
   Retesting of patients screened by the doctors turned up
irregularities that will require biopsies to determine if the five
women actually do have cancer, authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were also investigating the cases of some patients who
died after visiting the doctors - ''a handful,'' said state Health
Commissioner Dr. Antonia Novello. ''We are trying to obtain death
certificates.''
</P>
<P>
   In suspending the two doctors on May 31, Novello had said their
operation was ''a comedy of errors'' that left patients with poor
or inaccurate diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of the doctors' work showed they were finding an
average of 1.25 breast cancer cases per 1,000 screenings, a
fraction of the 5.15 cases found by the rest of the doctors in the
Healthy Women Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have since set up 3,500 exams for patients of the
two doctors, with 2,100 already rescreened, Novello said. Novello
acknowledged that the five women with possible cancer could have
developed the illness after they were tested by the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Bier's attorney, Barry Berke, said his client was ''confident he
will be completely cleared.'' DiBlasio's lawyer, Scott Einiger,
said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative hearings on the doctors' licenses are expected
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   One of the doctor's patients, 41-year-old Alma Amill of the
Bronx, has already filed a lawsuit against the pair alleging that
their misdiagnosis of her breast cancer led to a spread of the
disease and her mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   She began undergoing chemotherapy two weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
