<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP-Led Congress, Clinton Far Apart  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At first glance, the Republican-led Congress
appears to be moving forward on popular issues such as a new
Medicare prescription drug benefit and a big income tax cut for
most of America's married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, however, is that while some seeds of compromise
have been sown, election-year politics in most cases are likely to
block final agreement between lawmakers and President Clinton. Much
of this year's debate -- especially in the House, where Democrats
are battling for control -- is more to score political points than
create law.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Medicare prescription drugs. With much
fanfare, the House passed legislation last week that relies on a
blend of private insurance and federal subsidies to spread coverage
across the country. That is completely at odds with Clinton's
proposal for a government-run program for the 39 million Medicare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ''By legislative definition, an accomplishment isn't an
accomplishment until it becomes law,'' said House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. ''Under that definition, the passage of
prescription drug coverage legislation can at best be considered a
press release.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, on the other hand, say they are doing what voters
want: cutting taxes, paying down the federal debt, controlling
government spending. They contend it serves the political interests
of Democrats to resist compromise, then blame the GOP when the
bills don't become law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a list of accomplishments we can point to that's
good for the American people,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla.,
chairman of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   An example is the Senate GOP's bill to cut income taxes by $248
billion over 10 years for virtually all married couples, including
the 25 million who pay more than they would if single. Clinton and
congressional Democrats agree this is an unfair feature of the tax
code, but they have thrown up roadblock after roadblock. The most
recent obstacle was last week's offer by the president to sign the
bill only if an acceptable Medicare drug bill is also passed.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns from its Independence Day recess, Senate
GOP leaders say passage of the stand-alone ''marriage penalty''
bill will be their first order of business -- and it won't be linked
to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to go to the president,'' said Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. ''We're going to see whether he means
what he said in the State of the Union, that he wanted to get rid
of the marriage penalty tax.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some compromise is inevitable. Before the year is
out, Congress and Clinton almost certainly will agree on each of
the 13 spending bills needed to run government in the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1. They have agreed to lift the outside earnings
limit for Social Security recipients, force certain secretive
tax-exempt political organizations to report contributions and
expenditures and give electronic signatures the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Senate also is likely to send Clinton one of his
major priorities: a House-passed bill enacting permanent normal
trade relations with China. ''It's not a matter of if, but a matter
of when,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Many more major issues seem hopelessly deadlocked. The Senate
passed a patients' bill of rights last week that included a limited
right to sue HMOs, but Democrats say it is weak and are dead set
against it. Bills overhauling bankruptcy laws and repealing
inheritance taxes have drawn Clinton veto threats, and negotiations
on gun control and the minimum wage are bogged down. Nothing is
being done to brace Social Security and Medicare to pay for baby
boom retirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a session of Congress that's going to be
remembered for accomplishing a great deal if things don't pick
up,'' said Jack Lew, the White House budget director.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes both sides resort to a second-tier accomplishment to
substitute for something bigger. For instance, lawmakers and the
White House are rushing to embrace legislation ensuring that
surplus Medicare money isn't sidetracked for spending or tax cuts,
even though such legislation would do nothing to ensure the
program's future solvency and could easily be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite election-year difficulties, a chance of a breakthrough
always exists. In the 1996 election year, Clinton twice vetoed and
then signed a GOP welfare reform bill that gave both sides a major
accomplishment to bring to voters. That's something some
congressional candidates need this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we need to do is what the voters expect us to do,'' said
Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., a 30-year
veteran who is in a tough re-election fight against Delaware Gov.
Thomas Carper. ''That is to work together to achieve consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
