<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio campaign counterpunching  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The fledgling campaign of Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Republican rival for the Senate, Rep. Rick Lazio, is
relying heavily on a rapid response team whose mission is to
counterpunch until other weapons are in place.
</P>
<P>
   When Newsday reported Thursday that the first lady had attended
a fund-raiser for Democratic Rep. Eliot Engel on the night of June
15 in New Rochelle, the Lazio team swung into action.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Clinton and her supporters had been running
television advertisements attacking the Republican congressman from
Long Island for missing a House vote on that same night on a
measure to create a home heating oil reserve for the Northeast. The
measure failed by two votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had caught a late flight out of Washington so he could
keep to his campaign schedule the next day in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Engel and four other New York Democrats also
missed the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton had already raised hypocrisy to a fine art,''
said a statement from Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal Col sent to
reporters after the Newsday story appeared. ''This time she created
a masterpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again Mrs. Clinton says one thing, but does another,''
said state Republican Chairman William Powers in his own statement.
''She attacks Rick Lazio for missing a vote, but was raising money
for a Democrat that missed the same vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If hypocrisy was an Olympic event, Hillary would be a shoo-in
for the gold,'' chimed in Rep. Thomas Reynolds, a western New York
Republican, in his own news release.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton thinks she can be elected by deceiving New
York voters, but New Yorkers are a sophisticated electorate and
will reject her hypocrisy,'' state Conservative Party Chairman
Michael Long's statement said. The party's leadership has endorsed
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The same cast of characters went on the attack after word came
out June 22 that Lazio's profitable stock option trading in a
company run by some of his major campaign contributors was under
investigation by the federal Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton administration has a long history of abusing
federal authority and using government bureaucracies to attack
their political opponents,'' Dal Col said in a quickly issued news
release.
</P>
<P>
   Similar themes were evident in June 22 news releases out within
minutes from Powers, Reynolds and Long.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid response team represents something of a holding action
as the Lazio campaign struggles to get up to speed on fund raising,
scheduling and the many other details needed to run a smooth
statewide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got to look at it more as a battle and right now we are
freedom fighters, so we will carry on guerrilla activities in
numerous locations, going against the behemoth of the White House
and the Clinton spin machine,'' Dal Col said in a recent interview.
''I will put my sniper rifles in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col, a veteran of Long Island politics who ran millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes' two unsuccessful presidential campaigns,
said they will have to carry the battle until he can ''put my
Marines on the beach'' and ''start coming back in with the Army.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been campaigning across New York for a year,
Lazio didn't formally join the race until May 20, the day after
Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani quit the contest because of
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Lazio has had stumbles, such as the missed House
vote, that the Clinton campaign has been quick to seize on. Over
the past two weeks, the first lady and her supporters have launched
six TV ads attacking the congressman for that and other things.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just gotten into it,'' Clinton said Wednesday when asked
to explain what appears to be a strategy of relentless attacks.
''We have some ground to cover to catch up, to make sure that
voters have a good base of information to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid response team strategy being utilized by Lazio to
counter the first lady's attacks was perfected in 1992 by her
husband, Bill Clinton, during his first presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Marc Humbert has been covering New York politics for The
Associated Press for more than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
