<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Meriden, flap over trap rock development  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) - A plan to level a 100-foot-high hill of
trap rock to make way for a housing development is upsetting
environmentalists and pushing the city to sue its own planning
commission for approving the development.
</P>
<P>
   Meriden's planning commission has approved a proposal to build
36 townhouse units on the 12-acre site near Cathole Mountain, a
plan that requires leveling the hill to make way for a road.
</P>
<P>
   The developer, Community Village LLC, whose managing member is
Middletown businessman William Corvo, also wants to sell the
crushed, excavated trap rock.
</P>
<P>
   Meriden City Planner Dominic Caruso is appealing the
commission's vote, with the unanimous backing of the town council
and Mayor Joseph Marinan Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of those cases where a family is suing a family, so
to speak,'' Caruso said. ''I've never filed suit against a planning
commission before, but it's the only way to prevent what I think is
a total disregard of our regulations and a total disregard of the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is clouded by three city regulations. They include
an ordinance allowing earth excavation under certain circumstances,
and regulations allowing planned developments where the hill is
located. A third ordinance is designed to protect the ridge line.
</P>
<P>
   The developers argue that the hill is not technically part of
the ridge line, but opponents say the ridge-line protection law is
meant to protect the extended area, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''All three (sets of rules) are consistent in that they all
state that any development shall be done to accommodate the
existing natural features,'' Caruso said. ''If you're going to take
down the whole natural feature - I don't care if you call it a
knoll, a mountain or a hill - you're certainly not accommodating
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters say property owners must also be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sooner or later somebody is going to be able to develop that
land,'' said Lois Demayo, a planning commissioner who supported the
project. ''As a planning commissioner it really isn't my concern
who makes the money. I am just tired of government wanting to
control everything. If the city government wanted to control this
property, they should have purchased it when it was on the auction
block.''
</P>
<P>
   Corvo's lawyer said opponents are unfairly projecting their
fears of creeping development on Cathole Mountain onto his client's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they're really worried about (Corvo's) knoll. I
think they're worried about the future of Cathole Mountain,''
William Shea said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 1340 </TRAILER>
