<DOCNO> APW20000701.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Also moved in advance for release Sunday, July 2, and thereafter  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The first round of staffing cuts at St. Mary's
Hospital were the kind a patient might not notice immediately. It
takes a little longer to get the phone answered than it did a year
ago. Paperwork piles up for a few more days.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a round two, the cuts will be obvious and they will
be painful, promised Martin Morrissey, vice president of finance
for the Waterbury hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Staff cuts at St. Mary's and hospitals throughout Connecticut
can be traced to 1997's federal budget. The package dramatically
cut the amount hospitals receive for treatment of patients on
Medicare, the national insurance program for the elderly and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Since then there has been consensus on Capitol Hill that the
Medicare rate cuts went too deep. Last fall, Congress voted to
restore $16 billion to health care providers. But this year nothing
has been done.
</P>
<P>
   If that remains the case, there will be serious consequences for
Connecticut, promised Hartford Hospital Vice President Kevin
Kinsella.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question for a number of hospitals in Connecticut,
particularly some of the smaller ones, will be 'Can they survive?'
For hospitals that may be larger, the question is, 'What can we
afford to continue to offer in the way of services?'''
</P>
<P>
   Recent rumblings in Congress and from the White House indicate
help is on the way in the form of a cash infusion by the session's
end.
</P>
<P>
   Though desperately needed, the cash will do little to solve the
problem in the long run, said Joe Coatsworth, vice president for
government relations for the Connecticut Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   He fully expects the hospital association to come traipsing up
Capitol Hill several times next year, as it did this year, in
search of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the 1997 budget was to balance the country's
books for the first time in years. Medicare cuts, approximately $1
billion to Connecticut over five years, was one of the mechanisms
to do that.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, budget cutters believed hospitals would work with
private insurers and find other ways to supplement their budgets,
said Rep. Nancy Johnson, a New Britain Republican who serves on the
committee that funds Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also believed there was abundant waste in the system
that could be painlessly cut.
</P>
<P>
   ''As it turns out, we took a lot fat out of the system but we
also got a lot meat and bone,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn,
a member of the Senate's health committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it's time for some reconstructive surgery,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Without a budget boost Hartford residents would face shortened
hours for outpatient, behavioral health and dermatology clinics,
Kinsella said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We run a large service for people who can't afford to pay.
What happens if we can't is those individuals wind up in the
emergency room or the state has to provide the services
elsewhere?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's has already tried to eliminate psychiatric services
to save money, but the state wouldn't allow it because those
patients would have nowhere to turn, Morrissey said.
</P>
<P>
   The squeeze on hospitals can't be attributed entirely to
Medicare cuts. Managed care has capped hospital fees at levels that
aren't always sustainable, Coatsworth said. Medicaid, the
state-federal insurance program for the poor, pays hospitals less
than the actual cost of care and assumes those dollars will be made
up elsewhere, Kinsella said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has helped out by repealing a tax on gross hospitals
earnings - a move that saved the hospitals $92.5 million,
Coatsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   But as of late June no reimbursement bills had moved in the U.S.
House or Senate. Johnson attributed this in large part to President
Clinton's silence on the matter until recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year they used to say, 'There's a problem. We need to fix
it.' That helped things move along.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the month the White House did step in with a
proposal to boost Medicare payments by $21 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Johnson said she believes the change of heart
followed growing estimations of a federal budget surplus and
concluded there would be enough to both increase Medicare
reimbursements and pay for prescription drugs under the program.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd believes the administration simply realized the need.
''This is not about relief for the providers. It's really about
relief for the people they serve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the long term he suggests creating a formula built into law
that would allow for flexibility in Medicare payments depending on
need.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would tackle the problem by creating a board within the
Department of Health and Human Services. ''The board could set more
market-oriented rates by looking at what other people are
charging,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coatsworth hopes something will end the yearly begging sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somehow we either need to improve reimbursement or figure out
how to get the private sector involved in this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 1343 </TRAILER>
