<DOCNO> APW20000701.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OpSail's packed harbor will offer glimpse of an earlier NYC  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The flotilla of ships that will jam New York
Harbor on Independence Day is meant as a nautical kickoff for the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But for those with a little imagination, the celebration will
also offer a vivid reminder of an earlier era, when shipping was
the world's lifeblood and New York its favorite port.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 70,000 vessels are expected to join the weeklong
maritime festival, including more than 180 wind-powered ''tall
ships,'' modern warships and private yachts.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you squint your eyes and look just so, it will be what it
(once) was,'' said Peter Neill, president of the South Street
Seaport Museum in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   While New York is still the nation's commercial center, shipping
has long since ceded its place as the bridge connecting the city to
the world. Airplanes, highways and the Internet now play the role
that frigates and clippers once did.
</P>
<P>
   But a century and a half ago, access to the waterways made New
York's fortune. An advantageous location and perfect natural harbor
made it the place where America met the world to trade goods, ideas
and information.
</P>
<P>
   Ships, Neill said, ''literally lined the length of the East
River, and then the Hudson River as far as the eye could see. ...
Where the ships were, that's where the action took place.''
</P>
<P>
   With the completion of the Erie Canal in 1825, New York's role
as a mercantile center was cemented. It became a hub for the
exchange of textiles and other manufactured goods from newly
industrialized Europe, tea from China, grain from the Midwest, and
cotton and tobacco from the slave-holding South.
</P>
<P>
   On a single day in 1836, 921 vessels jammed the East River docks
and another 320 floated up the Hudson, according to ''New York: An
Illustrated History,'' by Ric Burns, James Sanders and Lisa Ades.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years later, shipping volume had tripled and the
vessels coming to New York from 150 foreign ports delivered half of
all American imports and departed with a third of the nation's
exports.
</P>
<P>
   The California Gold Rush fueled growth further, stuffing the
wallets of wealthy merchants and shipbuilders and forcing crews to
fight for dock space.
</P>
<P>
   Frontiersman Davy Crockett was shocked by the sheer volume of it
all when he visited in the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   ''The number of ships beat me all hollow, and looked for all the
world like a big clearing in the West with the dead trees all
standing,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping made the city's fortune and shaped its character,
bringing culture, news, ideas, lucre and immigrants - both willing
and enslaved.
</P>
<P>
   On South Street, the heart of the port district, ships' booms
reached over the road and nearly touched buildings on the other
side. Sailmakers' shops sat next to sailors' brothels, bars and
boarding houses.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the purveyors of rum, rope and sailcloth have been
replaced by modern-day merchants at the South Street Seaport, a
mall-by-the-water that draws throngs of tourists and lunching
workers from the nearby financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Upscale chain shops like Godiva Chocolatier, Ann Taylor and
Coach leathers now sit where sea captains once took shelter from
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The Seaport will recapture a hint of its ocean-going heyday
during OpSail 2000, when it showcases some of the most impressive
of the parading tall ships.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes just a glance out at the water to show anyone who
cares to look what won New York its place in the world - a vast,
protected harbor that still draws ships and barges from every
continent.
</P>
<P>
   And Neill says that although the trappings of the Seaport have
changed over the decades, its essence isn't really so different
from what it was in the 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Commerce always took place here,'' he said. ''Fashion and
gifts and goods were always being sold.''
</P>
<P>
   And overhead, the sleek glass skyscrapers are a reminder that
business and bustle - different today than in the seagoing era, but
with the same bottom line - remain the city's lifeblood.
</P>
<P>
   ''A place where trade and immigration come together is a
tremendous formula for invention,'' the historian said. ''That's
what the city did and that's what it's doing. And that's what it's
going to continue to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 1413 </TRAILER>
