<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Takes Over EU Presidency  </HEADLINE>
By DEBORAH SEWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Seaside summits in swank resorts are the main stage
for France's six-month presidency of the European Union, but its
hopes for a no-waves term are being swept away by a deepening
debate over the union's political future.
</P>
<P>
   The union of 15 European nations has a rotating presidency, and
France took over Saturday, replacing Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   French leaders have said they want to focus on institutional
reforms during the country's term -- hardly headline-grabbing
issues, but vital if the EU is to be able to function once it
expands to as many as 30 members within the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer's
daring proposal for EU nations to go beyond tinkering with current
institutions: He suggested the creation of a European federal
government with a constitution. The idea has unsettled Europe's
political elite and France's plan for a no-nonsense presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will probably have the busiest presidency in the last ten
years or so and ... the biggest stakes,'' Pierre Moscovici, the
French minister for European affairs, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's lengthy summer holidays kicked off Saturday, so serious
work will not begin until early September. That leaves French
leaders less than four months to complete a hefty agenda.
</P>
<P>
   One area of focus will be institutional reform. Without changes
to streamline operations, the EU runs the risk that its
decision-making process would be paralyzed when it nearly doubles
in size.
</P>
<P>
   One measure under consideration would scrap the current
arrangement under which EU decisions have to be unanimous and
instead use a majority vote on all but the most vital issues.
Another proposal would change the ways seats are allocated on the
influential 20-member EU commission, the union's executive board.
</P>
<P>
   France wants to make sure Europe's big countries continue to
have a major say in EU affairs. It wants to restrict the use of the
veto, where one country can block an issue favored by the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of French leaders is to have those primary
institutional reforms wrapped up by the EU summit in Nice in
December.
</P>
<P>
   However, a number of other issues linger: Fischer's bold speech
in May, growing unhappiness among EU applicants over the way
enlargement is being handled, the debate about whether to keep EU
sanctions against Austria for allowing a right-wing party into
government. Such items threaten to saddle the French with just what
they wanted to avoid -- controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In what he called a ''personal vision'' of the future of Europe,
Fischer said he wanted to see the formation of a ''center of
gravity,'' a kind of core group of nations that would agree to give
the EU stronger political powers.
</P>
<P>
   The speech triggered powerful -- and contradictory -- reactions in
France. Some vehemently opposed it, but it found an ally in French
President Jacques Chirac, a conservative and one-time Euroskeptic
who only recently has endorsed stronger political ties for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Berlin this week, Chirac took up Fischer's themes
and proposed creating a ''pioneer group'' to forge closer political
ties among participating nations.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a ''two-speed Europe,'' however, is viewed
skeptically by Britain, Ireland and Scandinavian nations. Other
smaller EU nations also worry they would be dominated by the larger
ones.
</P>
<P>
   France, meanwhile, just wants to make sure such questions don't
block more incremental progress.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio interview Friday, Moscovici warned other European
nations not ''to compromise'' the French presidency ''by
overloading the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's not add debates ... that we can't deal with,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 1459 </TRAILER>
