<HEADLINE> Former Brazil Congressman Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A judge has sentenced a former
congressman already convicted of murder and financial crimes to 14
years in prison for distributing drugs in exchange for votes, media
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Hildebrando Pascoal, a former colonel in the Acre state police,
was sentenced Friday by Judge Regina Longuini in Rio Branco, 1,900
miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro, Estado news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   While running for Congress in 1998, Pascoal distributed an
unspecified amount of illegal drugs to residents in the Acre state
who vowed to vote for him, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, another judge found Pascoal guilty in
the murders of a police officer and a firefighter killed in 1997.
It was unclear what his sentence was then. But in March, the same
judge sentenced Pascoal to more than six years in prison for tax
fraud and other financial crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials could not be reached for comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Pascoal, who has been in jail since September, was expelled from
Congress and stripped of his parliamentary immunity after witnesses
testified that he led death squads and a drug trafficking ring in
Acre, which shares a remote jungle border with Bolivia and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   He still faces additional charges that include kidnapping and
international drug trafficking, court officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 other active and former police officers, hired
gunmen and former subordinates of Pascoal were arrested last year
and await trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
