<HEADLINE> Busta Rhynes Demands Loyalty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Busta Rhymes is a hard-driving boss, and if
there's one thing the rapper and actor demands without a sliver of
space for error it's absolute, unwavering loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   And he gives it right back, just like his character in the new
movie ''Shaft,'' a cabby who's Samuel Jackson's right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the right role for me to be doing because it shows
people, especially nowadays, man, that whoever you riding with you
need to be loyal to,'' Busta Rhymes, aka Trevor Smith, says in the
August issue of Vibe magazine.
</P>
<P>
   With his own proteges in his Flipmode Entertainment -- Rah Digga,
Spliff Star and Rock Macy among them -- the 28-year-old is a
tireless promoter, jumping on stage during their solo outings and
plugging them at his own appearances, even during the Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Flipmode Squad, we obligate ourselves to each other,''
the rapper said. ''We can't do shows if everybody don't show up; we
might lose money if everybody don't show up. So I felt like ...
everybody gotta love each other somehow, appreciate each other to a
point where commitment ain't even something we gotta ask for from
each other.''
</P>
