<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers report good growing season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A year after a crippling drought destroyed
corn crops across the Garden State, area farmers are reporting a
strong growing season.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 months from August 1998 through July 1999 were the
fifth-driest, one-year stretch of the century. As a result, last
summer farmers were stuck with shrunken rows of corn that never
matured.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, ample rain and stretches of hot weather
should help farmers rebound, the Courier-Post of Cherry Hill
reported for Saturday's editions. Many farmers began picking their
sweet corn last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just about right,'' John Hunter, 52, said as he surveyed his
family's corn crops in Cinnaminson Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Three generations of Hunters work the fields these days, many
picking the sweet corn by hand. While the family also has tractors
to help with picking, 80-year-old Russell Hunter said the machines
often damage the ears, reducing their appeal to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The family has been planting sweet corn since April - 20 to 40
rows at a time - so it will have plenty of fresh corn for its
roadside stand.
</P>
<P>
   Corn ranks third statewide among vegetable crops in terms of
farmers' revenues. New Jersey grows about 10,600 acres of sweet
corn, with Salem and Burlington counties producing the most.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey farmers usually grow a kind of sweet corn called
''sugar-extended,'' which is sweeter and lasts slightly longer
after picking than the once-dominant silver queen variety, said Ray
Samulis, a Burlington County agricultural agent.
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers prefer the taste of ''sugar extended'' over ''super
sweet,'' which lasts four or five days after picking but has a
tougher skin and less ''corn'' flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It used to be you pretty much had to eat sweet corn the day it
was picked for it to be really good,'' Samulis said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the rest of the country, which favors yellow corn, most
of the sweet corn grown in New Jersey is white.
</P>
<P>
   Samulis said he can't explain the preference, but thinks a
warming effect from the Atlantic Ocean and Delaware River helps
produce great sweet corn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
