<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. MD Charged With Manslaughter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACE, Fla. (AP) -- A doctor has been charged with manslaughter
after he allegedly over-prescribed powerful narcotics to numerous
patients, including four who died.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James F. Graves, a family practitioner who specializes in
pain management, also was charged with racketeering and
drug-trafficking for allegedly providing thousands of pills to
known drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs he allegedly overprescribed included Oxycontin, a
synthetic morphine, Lortab, a painkiller, and Xanax, a
tranquilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Graves surrendered Friday, hours after a grand jury issued its
indictment. He was being held Saturday at the Santa Rosa County
jail in lieu of $500,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum sentences he faces are 30 years for racketeering, 30
years each for three counts of trafficking and 15 years on each of
the four counts of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Stewart, Graves' attorney, called the charges ''a bunch of
nonsense'' and said prosecutors are abusing their power.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every doctor and every patient of every doctor needs to follow
this case,'' Stewart said. ''The State Attorney's Office does not
have the power to even discipline a doctor for giving out too much
aspirin. For them to proceed as they have is frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves is charged with manslaughter for the 1999 deaths of Anne
Carroll, Jeffrey Daniels and Gwen Carpenter and the March death of
Howard Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they interviewed pharmacists and pharmacy
technicians who said they refused to fill Graves' prescriptions
because they were excessive in amount and frequency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
