<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State to move 25 sex offenders to Trenton  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - About 25 sex offenders from Greystone Park
Psychiatric Hospital will be transferred to a center here, a move
in response to years of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Space has been set aside for 50 beds in a new wing at the Anne
Klein Forensic Center, said Laurie Facciarossa, a spokeswoman for
the state Department of Human Services. Facciarossa said the move
is an attempt to reduce the population at the troubled Greystone
facility, where 600 patients are housed.
</P>
<P>
   State officials in the past have placed at Greystone sex
offenders who have maxed out their jail terms but are still
considered dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   That policy has long angered people who live near the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Morris County officials have said because the
hospital doesn't have security as would a prison, people can
escape, creating danger to public. One sex offender escaped from
Greystone in October and another was charged with raping a male
patient at the hospital in January.
</P>
<P>
   Human Services Commissioner Michele Guhl in March promised
Morris County freeholders that the sex offenders would be moved.
She also said she would uphold an administrative order barring sex
offenders registered under Megan's Law from being kept at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the transfers should begin July 17.
Patients from Ancora Psychiatric Hospital in Camden and other
hospitals also may be sent to the center in the future, officials
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
