<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DOE: Preparation Helped Battle Fire  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA ASHTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- Preparation was crucial to the battle
against the fire that raced across the Hanford nuclear reservation,
storage site for some of the most lethal wastes on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation releases and the spread of hazardous contamination are
big risks, but the Department of Energy has been exhaustive in
getting ready for possible emergencies on the 560-square-mile site,
established during World War II to make plutonium for the atomic
bomb, said Larry Olguin, site emergency director.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not want to ever try to downplay the significance of
the danger of a range fire,'' he said. ''But the fact that it
burned over 190,000 acres and no known radiation releases occurred
didn't happen by chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The blaze, started Tuesday by a fatal highway accident,
destroyed 20 homes and scores of other buildings. At its peak late
Wednesday, about 7,000 people were evacuated. One man suffered
serious burns and more than a dozen people were treated for smoke
inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   The wildfire was essentially out Saturday. All firefighters
should be sent home by Sunday, said interagency fire manager Dale
Warriner.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said air samples had not indicated any radiation
releases caused by the blaze. The U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency was conducting additional tests during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Olguin said the emergency preparations allowed crews to move
safely into sensitive areas to provide spot fire protection where
needed. Many sites at the complex had previously been cleared of
vegetation, and roads provided firebreaks.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford's most lethal wastes are stored six feet underground in
177 giant tanks that were kept safe from the flames. Other
radioactive waste produced over more than four decades was poured
into the ground or stored in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   People around Hanford are keenly aware of the threat posed by
those tanks filled with 54 million gallons of highly radioactive
sludge.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was kind of a scary thing,'' said Greg Alley of Richland,
who works at Siemens Power Corp., which fabricates commercial
nuclear fuel. ''The fire getting into those areas, that's a fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind-driven fire, moving as fast as 20 miles in 90 minutes,
pushed dangerously close to the tank farms in some areas, though
the DOE could not say Saturday just how close.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were very concerned, and we were at an extremely high
attention level for the fire, especially Wednesday night,'' Olguin
said. ''Had the wind shifted, it could have been worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 1723 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Youth Call For Tolerance  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Hoping to heal the ethnic wounds that brought
on a government takeover six weeks ago, a group of indigenous
Fijian youths hugged and shook hands with ethnic Indians Saturday
and called for greater tolerance on the South Pacific island
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen Fijians, representing Christian youth groups,
staged a day of fasting and prayer Saturday in a park in the
capital, Suva. The city has watched during the past 43 days as
gunmen took over the nation's ethnic Indian-led government; they
continued Saturday to hold 27 lawmakers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's surround our Indian brothers and sisters with our
Christian love,'' group leader Mika Yasa Mudreilagi said as people
hugged and sobbed. ''Please forgive us for any hurt that we have
caused you.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, gunmen led by former insurance executive George
Speight stormed Parliament and took the government hostage,
including deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, the first
ethnic Indian to lead Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was accompanied by widespread attacks on Indian homes
and businesses across Fiji, a nation of 320 islands about 2,250
miles northeast of Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   About 44 percent of Fiji's 812,000 people are ethnic Indians
whose ancestors were brought here more than a century ago by
British colonialists seeking indentured laborers to work in the
country's rich sugarcane fields.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel raid and hostage standoff have raised concern in the
international community that Fiji has descended into racism and
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Speight and the military -- which imposed martial
law 10 days after the parliament raid -- broke down this week after
the gunmen refused to sign an accord that would pave the way for
the immediate release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The military then announced that they would appoint an interim
civilian government without input from the hostage-takers, who had
demanded a role in the administration before releasing the
captives.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rebels' demands to disenfranchise Fiji's Indians
have been met, including the firing of Chaudhry and the elimination
of the country's 1997 multiracial constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
