<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Pressure Mounts in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- On the eve of a tight presidential race,
observers and opposition activists Saturday stepped up accusations
against Mexico's ruling party -- charging it with using the power of
the state to illegally influence voting.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations involved scattered incidents, small amounts of
money or claims of pressure on government employees or aid
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, dismissed most of the reports as misunderstandings or the
result of newspapers' desperation for stories in the three-day
period before the election, when candidates are banned from
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Mexico City newspaper Reforma published what it
said were excerpts of a phone conversation showing Victor Tinoco,
PRI governor of the western state of Michoacan, discussing
''donations'' from the government to party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Tinoco told The Associated Press that he hadn't passed on any
state money and said the tape was fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is totally false, and if the newspaper thinks it's real,
let's go to court and I'll defend myself,'' Tinoco said by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern state of Sinaloa, opposition activists filmed
alleged government aid workers pressing aid recipients to support
PRI presidential candidate Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Development Secretariat, which runs the anti-poverty
program, said the people shown in the film had not worked for the
government in at least six months.
</P>
<P>
   ''In rural areas, the inhabitants see someone as a 'government
employee,' and that image sticks with them'' even after they leave
government service, secretariat spokesman Humberto Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, electoral officials in the border state of Sonora
said they requested a criminal investigation after finding one of
the ballots for Sunday's election already had been filled out in
favor of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The observer group Civic Alliance said a disturbingly high
number of volunteer poll officials have been changed in the last
few days before elections, a phenomenon that has been associated
with fraud in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In past elections, critics have accused local PRI workers of
paying poll officials not to show up on election day so they could
be replaced with loyalists who would tolerate fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''About 19 percent of poll officials have been substituted so
far,'' said Hugo Almada of the alliance. ''That's a higher figure
than in past elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Almada also said his group has seen increased pressure on
government employees to vote for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper La Jornada on Saturday quoted employees of the
Foreign Relations Secretariat as saying a supervisor had told them
to press co-workers and family members to vote for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The secretariat had no immediate comment on the accusations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
