<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State finds no violations in pool drowning at College of NJ  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EWING, N.J. (AP) - State swimming pool regulations were not
violated the night a Princeton Township man was found dead in the
water at the College of New Jersey, according to a state report.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Morris, 48, was found dead in the school's Aquatic
Center on the night of June 7. A student scuba diver found the
corpse. Medical examiners said Morris' death was caused by a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the state Department of Health and Senior Services
said there were no violations of state regulations that may have
contributed to Morris' death, The Times of Trenton reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The report was filed June 9, but state officials later said they
were still investigating the death. Dennis McGowan, spokesman for
the Department of Health and Senior Services, told the newspaper
Friday that the agency was satisfied that no state codes were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report filed by the school, the lifeguard on duty
did not follow standard procedure, but that did ''not appear to
have contributed'' to Morris' death.
</P>
<P>
   The lone guard on duty when the body was found was not watching
the pool, but was cleaning up the pool area, the report said. Also,
earlier that night, guards did not sit in their stands, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
   State regulations on waterfront safety require that lifeguards
''shall not be subject to duties that would distract or intrude
their attention from proper observation of person(s) in the pool
area, or that prevent immediate assistance to person(s) in distress
in the water,'' the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ''lifeguard platforms or stands should be elevated and
located at the water's edge so as to provide a clear unobstructed
view of the pool surface and bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   The state report said lifeguards would not have been able to see
Morris' body under a bulkhead in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' body was found about 9:30 p.m. He had been swimming
during an open session that ended at 9 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 1758 </TRAILER>
