<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police spot break-in while testing new video monitors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - State Police testing out a new video
security system got proof that it works, they said, when the
cameras caught a man breaking into the system installer's car.
</P>
<P>
   Mason Covington, 36, of Trenton, was breaking into the car in
the Department of State parking lot Friday afternoon as police
tested the system, said State Police spokesman Sgt. Al Della Fave.
</P>
<P>
   Security company employees had finished installing the system
just minutes before the break-in and were showing security guards
how the cameras worked when they saw the burglar.
</P>
<P>
   Covington grabbed a laptop computer, a briefcase filled with
computer accessories and a wallet with cash and credit cards, Della
Fave said. He was caught minutes later in a nearby alley and
everything was recovered, he said. Covington faces charges of
burglary and receiving stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   State Police have been asking the state for years for money to
put aerial cameras outside the buildings near the Statehouse.
Before the new system was installed Friday, police had to rely on
foot and vehicle patrols.
</P>
</TEXT>
