<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glory Days for Mets' Leiter  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- They were dancing in the aisles so much at Shea
Stadium on Saturday it seemed like a Springsteen concert -- which is
exactly where Al Leiter was heading.
</P>
<P>
   His 100th career win, a season-high 12 strikeouts and the final
concert of Bruce's tour, all in the same day. Not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had my Springsteen tickets for about a month,'' Leiter
said after the Mets beat the Braves 9-1. ''When I saw I was down to
pitch, I knew it was going to be a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter came out to the mound for the start of the game to ''10th
Avenue Freeze-out.''
</P>
<P>
   When he batted, the public address system played ''Born to
Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, he went 1-for-3 and did circle the bases to score a run,
allowing one run and six hits in seven innings. He raised his
record to 10-1 and lowered his ERA to 3.04, third in the NL behind
Randy Johnson (1.57) and Kevin Brown (2.31).
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has been to four or five Springsteen shows, starting with
the 1984-85 ''Born in the USA'' tour and attending one with a
couple of Yankees during the 1988 ''Tunnel of Love'' tour. Leiter
said the Boss -- Springsteen, not Steinbrenner -- didn't want to talk
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was more interested in Don Mattingly,'' Leiter recalled
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was all smiles after Saturday's win, which solidified his
chance to make the National League's All-Star pitching staff, which
will be announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't think back to last October, when he started Game 6 of
the NL championship series at Atlanta and gave up five runs without
getting anyone out. While the Mets rallied to take 8-7 and 9-8
leads, they lost 10-9 in 11 innings, ending their season.
</P>
<P>
   When Leiter walked into Shea Stadium on Saturday morning, he was
still on a high from Friday night's 11-8 win, when the Mets rallied
from an 8-1, eighth-inning deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be pretty tough to contain what happened last
night,'' Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't even there to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter left Shea Stadium when the eighth inning began, drove
back to Manhattan and was about to pull into his garage when he
heard Edgardo Alfonzo's game-tying, two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Since Leiter didn't want to lose the radio signal by driving his
car into the underground garage, he waited in his car, on the
corner of 83rd Street and First Avenue and listened to Gary Cohen's
call of Mike Piazza's three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter quickly parked and went upstairs to his apartment to
watch the replays.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was pretty up today,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 1851 </TRAILER>
