<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Party Pressure Mounts in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- On the eve of a tight presidential race, observers and
opposition activists today stepped up accusations against Mexico's ruling party
-- charging it with using the power of the state to illegally influence voting.
The allegations involved scattered incidents, small amounts of money or claims
of pressure on government employees or aid recipients. Officials of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party dismissed most of the reports as
misunderstandings or the result of newspapers' desperation for stories.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Terrace Collapses in Ohio, 80 Injured
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS, Ohio (AP) -- A terrace at an island winery in Lake Erie
collapsed this afternoon, injuring at least 80 people authorities said. The
terrace collapsed at the Lonz Winery on an island about 5 miles off the
mainland. A dispatcher at the police department in nearby Port Clinton said the
collapse occurred about 5 p.m. He said about 60 firefighters and emergency
medical personnel were on their way to the island. Middle Bass is about 50 miles
east of Toledo.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gas Prices High, Holiday Travel Still Heavy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- High gas prices are slimming holiday travelers' wallets a bit
more than usual, but it doesn't seem to be stopping drivers from taking to the
road this weekend. ''It's the Fourth of July weekend. What are you going to do
-- stay home? Plans are all on,'' said Tom Woody of Madison, Wisc., as he filled
up his tank en route to a paddling trip in southern Wisconsin.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indiana's Ten Commandments Law Used
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PAOLI, Ind. (AP) -- Shrugging off the threat of lawsuits, Orange County
officials became the first in the state to take advantage of a new Indiana law
that allows government entities to post the Ten Commandments. Renditions of
''God Bless America'' and scripture readings echoed from the steps of the county
courthouse today as nearly 300 people who began gathering just before midnight
watched officials unveil a plaque with the religious tenets the moment the new
law went into effect.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Actor Walter Matthau Dies at 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Walter Matthau, an Oscar-winning actor who once
portrayed villains but moved on to become the epitome of a crotchety comedian,
died early today of a heart attack. He was 79. Matthau was pronounced dead at
1:42 a.m. at St. John's Health Center in Santa Monica, the hospital said. ''I
have lost someone I loved as a brother, as a closest friend and a remarkable
human being,'' frequent co-star Jack Lemmon said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gay Couples Legally Join in Vermont
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) -- Vermont's new civil union law took effect
today, and gay couples around the state were legally joined before justices of
the peace and clergy. ''I think it's about time after 27&AMP;frac12; years,'' said
Lois Farnham, her arm around partner Holly Puterbaugh after they got their civil
union license. ''It's nice after all this time to say Holly is my spouse.''
Puterbaugh, 54, and Farnham, 55, were one of three couples who sued in 1997 when
their town clerks refused to issue them marriage licenses.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
10 Iran Jews Convicted of Spying
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran (AP) -- A judge convicted 10 Iranian Jews of spying for Israel
and sentenced them to prison terms of four to 13 years Saturday, drawing
condemnation from Israel and President Clinton. Three other Jewish defendants
were acquitted of the same charges. Two Muslim accomplices were given more
lenient jail terms of only two years each, according to Hossein Ali Amiri, the
provincial judiciary chief. Two other Muslims were acquitted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pakistan Bans Child Death Sentences
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan introduced sweeping legal reforms on
Saturday, including changes to a law that allowed children as young as 14 to be
sentenced to death. The death penalty now may only be imposed against people 18
or older, the military-led government decreed. Also, accused children will not
be physically punished, handcuffed, or placed in chains -- except when there is
''reasonable apprehension of the escape of the child.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds-Diamondbacks Game Injury Filled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. was lifted for a pinch-hitter in the fifth
inning of today's game between Cincinnati and Arizona after he twisted his right
knee in center field in the fourth. The Reds also lost second baseman Pokey
Reese, who left after being hit in the left wrist by a pitch from Armando
Reynoso leading off the fifth. X-rays were negative. The Reds said both Griffey
and Reese would be evaluated on a day-to-day basis. Arizona rookie first baseman
Alex Cabrera, who was 3-for-3 with three RBIs, pulled up lame with a left groin
strain while running out an RBI double in the fourth.
</P>
