<HEADLINE> Mexicans Return Home to Vote  </HEADLINE>
By BART JONES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For the first time in 18 years, Juan Ramon
Alvarez is returning to his native Mexico to vote in a presidential
election. He wants to break the governing party's 71-year grip on
power.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez is one of many Mexicans from California to New York who
have been captivated by the neck-and-neck race between Francisco
Labastida of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party and
Vicente Fox of the center-right National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands were expected to cross the border in hopes of casting
one of a limited number of absentee ballots. Alvarez planned to
join a pre-dawn caravan from Los Angeles to Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The voters' impact on politics back home has not been lost on
the politicians. Mexican presidential candidates campaigned in the
United States and took out ads in Spanish-language media here.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties even pledged to give three at-large seats in
Mexico's Congress to Mexican nationals in Los Angeles and Chicago.
Whether the Mexican nationals actually fill the seats depends on
how the opposition parties fare in Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
   The wooing by the parties is ''an unprecedented outreach into
the Mexican immigrant community,'' said Harry Pachon, president of
the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute near Los Angeles. ''This is a new
stage in Mexican political development.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez wants to vote the governing party, known as the PRI, out
of office.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PRI has corrupted, up and down, left and right, the whole
society,'' he said. ''Finally we should decapitate the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   In East Los Angeles on Saturday, Ramon Barreto prepared to lead
a caravan of Mexicans who mostly support Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Barreto said he and his wife have been driving three hours to
the border to vote in presidential elections since 1982. But this
weekend, he expected to lead a caravan of 50 cars and 200 people.
He invited most of them to spend the night at a ranch he owns in
Tecate, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want change for all my people,'' Barreto said inside the
huge pinata and party supplies store he owns. ''Now is our big
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   About a tenth of Mexican adults -- 7 million to 10 million people
-- live in the United States. Los Angeles, with 2 million Mexicans,
has the world's largest concentration after Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1.5 million Mexicans in the United States hold Mexican
voting cards, said Felipe Aguirre, head of the U.S. campaign for
presidential candidate Cuahtemoc Cardenas of the leftist Democratic
Revolution Party.
</P>
<P>
   Absentee ballot voting abroad is not permitted, but Mexicans in
the United States hope that will change by the next congressional
elections in 2003. That would send the number of voters soaring,
Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans here also are wielding increasing economic clout. They
wire home at least $7 billion a year -- Mexico's third-largest
source of legal income after oil and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cardenas and Fox campaigned this year in California.
Labastida, who polls show in a statistical tie with Fox, met in
Tijuana with Mexican-American leaders. He also paid for an
eight-page insert in Spanish-language newspapers in Los Angeles,
San Antonio and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the caravans, opposition parties have established phone
banks so Mexicans can call home to urge relatives to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans traveling to the border to cast absentee ballots may
not get to vote. They are limited to 64 special booths set up along
the border with just 750 paper ballots per booth.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties charge that the PRI has limited the number of
special polling places and ballots along the border to reduce the
number of Mexicans in the United States who vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them are expected to vote against the PRI, which many
blame for Mexico's rampant corruption and widespread poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 1901 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
