<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard confiscates 125 kilograms of cocaine from Liberian freighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Coast Guard boarding party inspecting a
Liberian freighter with a damaged propeller found 125 kilograms of
cocaine hidden on board, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Timashevsk, a 593-foot hazardous material freighter, had
struck a navigation buoy Friday night as it was leaving New York
Harbor for Venezuela, said Coast Guard spokesman Petty Officer
Angelo Patti. The ship returned to Stapleton anchorage, which is
next to the Staten Island ferry dock on Staten Island, where the
Coast Guard discovered the drugs during a routine inspection around
11 a.m. Saturday, Patti said.
</P>
<P>
   The cocaine has a street value between $3.5 million and $5
million, Patti said. It was confiscated by U.S. Customs agents.
</P>
<P>
   None of the ship's crew were charged because the drugs were
found in a compartment on the outer section of the ship's stern,
which is normally underwater. The compartment was above the water
line Saturday because the ship's freight had already been unloaded
and it was riding higher in the water. That made it unclear to
investigators whether the crew knew the drugs were there, Patti
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The crew members are getting drug tested and the rudder is
being inspected, and if everything checks out, they'll be on their
way,'' Patti said. ''Normally all of these guys would have been
arrested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
