<HEADLINE> Yankees 6, Devil Rays 1  </HEADLINE>
By FRED GOODALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Tino Martinez broke an 0-for-15
slump with a single and three-run double Saturday that helped
Orlando Hernandez and the struggling New York Yankees beat the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   With owner George Steinbrenner in attendance, the Yankees won
for only the third time in nine games. He also got to see a
bench-clearing brawl, started when Tampa Bay's Bobby Smith tangled
with catcher Jorge Posada.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (7-6) returned to the rotation after missing two
scheduled starts because of a sprained right elbow. That problem
contributed to his shortest outing of the season against the
Chicago White Sox on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   The New York ace allowed four hits, including Smith's solo
homer, in 5 2-3 innings to snap a personal two-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Posada were ejected in the seventh inning when they
exchanged blows after Smith struck out on a check swing.
</P>
<P>
   The two bumped as Posada moved forward with the ball and Smith
crossed the plate on his way back to the dugout. The catcher spun
and shoved Smith before the Devil Rays' third baseman retaliated by
throwing a punch and wrestling Posada to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Both benches emptied, but order was restored quickly and no
other players entered the altercation as participants.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who was 2-for-5, is just 9-for-45 through the first 12
games of a season-long, 13-game road trip that ends Sunday. But his
bases-loaded double off Mark Guthrie broke the game open after the
Yankees wasted numerous opportunities to build on a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill doubled twice and drove in one run off Albie Lopez
(4-6). Shane Spencer and Derek Jeter added RBI singles for New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams has hit safely in every game on the Yankees road
trip, going 23-for-51 (.451) with five homers and 15 RBIs. He
singled in the second to extend his streak to 12 games and scored
on Spencer's RBI hit, then singled and scored on Martinez's double
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez struck out the side in the third, but allowed doubles to
Jose Vizcaino and O'Neill that produced New York's second run.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays starter got out of a bases-loaded jam in the
fifth when Posada flied to deep center, however the Yankees finally
drove him out of the game when Martinez singled and Spencer double
to open the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Rick White replaced Lopez and retired Scott Brosius on a
grounder to first before striking out Vizcaino escaping without
allowing a run when Bubba Trammell made a nice running catch on
Derek Jeter's drive to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Through six innings, the Yankees stranded nine runners and were
2-for-11 with men in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez improved to 5-1 against the Devil Rays, with the lone
loss coming on May 11 when he limited Tampa Bay to seven hits in a
1-0 complete-game loss to Steve Trachsel. He walked one and struck
out three after allowing nine runs in 2-3 of an inning in a 17-4
loss to the White Sox two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Choate replaced him, making his major league debut, with
one on and two outs in the sixth. The left-hander called up from
Triple-A Columbus on Thursday and retired the only batter he faced,
Fred McGriff, on a fly to center.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Yankees 2B Chuck Knoblauch was scratched from the starting
lineup because of a left ear infection. He was replaced by
Vizcaino, who batted leadoff and went 2-for-3 with a double and
triple ... Devil Rays 3B coach Billy Hatcher was ejected in the
third inning after reacting to 3B umpire C.B. Bucknor ruling a
check swing a strike against Randy Winn ... Jeter fouled off eight
straight pitches before taking a called third strike in the third
inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
