<HEADLINE> American League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   After breezing through the Oakland Athletics'
powerful lineup
for eight innings, Brian Cooper saved his best pitches for last.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rookie right-hander defied his pitch count and silenced the
Athletics' big bats in the Anaheim Angels' 7-0 victory Friday
night, his first major league shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ''I threw a few too many pitches in the eighth, and they said,
'Look, you've only got a few more pitches,''' said Cooper, who
scattered three hits -- all singles -- against the team ranked fourth
in the AL with 117 homers. ''I knew if I put anybody else on base,
I was done. So I just tried to throw it right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper (3-2) already had thrown 113 pitches when he entered the
ninth. But he struck out Ramon Hernandez, retired Terrence Long on
a flyball and got Randy Velarde to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was certainly going to be his last hitter. We were close
to taking him out,'' said manager Mike Scioscia, who had Al Levine
warming up.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper ended a string of three consecutive no-decisions and a
personal five-game winless streak in his first major league
complete game. He struck out four and walked one in his 13th career
start, giving the Angels their second shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In other AL games, Tampa Bay beat New York 6-4; Minnesota
defeated Cleveland 7-2; Chicago topped Boston 10-4; Baltimore beat
Toronto 8-3; Detroit edged Kansas City 3-1; and Texas routed
Seattle 13-3.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's shutout was preserved early by Garret Anderson, who
turned 28 on Friday. Anderson homered to trigger Anaheim's five-run
sixth inning and robbed Randy Velarde of a home run in the fourth
to keep the score at 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think it would go that far,'' Anderson said. ''But I
knew when I got to the wall that I had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland managed just Jason Giambi's first-inning single, a
fifth-inning single by Matt Stairs off first baseman Mo Vaughn's
glove and John Jaha's eighth-inning infield single.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just threw strikes with everything he had,'' Athletics
manager Art Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led off the sixth with his 22nd homer, one more than
his previous career best, and Bengie Molina homered one out later.
Adam Kennedy then doubled and scored on a single by Darin Erstad to
give the Angels a 5-0 lead and chase Mark Mulder (5-3), who allowed
six runs and 10 hits in 5 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Benji Gil greeted T.J. Mathews with the Angels' third homer of
the inning and the Angels' 123rd of the season -- the most they've
had before the All-Star break in the team's 40-year history. It
also was their 75th at home, one more than they hit at Edison Field
all last year.
Devil Rays 6, Yankees 4:
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay finished the best month in franchise history at 15-11,
while struggling New York closed out its first losing month since
August 1996 at 10-15.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Johnson, who hit a two-run single and walked four times,
got the game-winning RBI when Jeff Nelson (6-2) walked him on four
pitches with two outs and the bases loaded in the eighth. Todd
Erdos replaced Nelson and walked Felix Martinez to force in another
run. The visiting Yankees issued 11 walks.
Twins 7, Indians 2:
</P>
<P>
   Matt Lawton hit two home runs, and visiting Minnesota sent
Cleveland to its third straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   Midre Cummings, who also homered, Corey Koskie and Lawton each
had three of the Twins' 16 hits. Lawton hit a two-run homer in the
first inning off Jim Brower (2-2) and led off the sixth with a
homer off Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Redman (5-3) won for the first time since May 30.
White Sox 10, Red Sox 4:
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas and Brook Fordyce each homered twice for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas hit a solo homer in the fifth off Bryce Florie and added
another solo drive an inning later off Rheal Cormier. Fordyce hit a
solo shot in the fifth and a two-run shot in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Parque (8-2) won his fifth straight decision. Hipolito
Pichardo (2-1) lasted only four innings for visiting Boston.
Orioles 8, Blue Jays 3:
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle and Harold Baines had two RBIs apiece in a six-run
third inning, and Pat Rapp (5-5) earned his first win in a month as
Baltimore ended a 13-game losing streak against visiting Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Carlos Delgado went 0-for-4, ending his 22-game
hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Halladay (3-5) yielded seven runs, four hits and four walks
in 2 2-3 innings, his shortest stint as a starter this season.
Tigers 3, Royals 1:
</P>
<P>
   After allowing only four hits and no runs for eight innings,
Jeff Weaver (5-6) gave up consecutive singles to Johnny Damon and
pinch-hitter Mark Quinn in the ninth, but Detroit held on to win at
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Jones gave up an RBI single to Mike Sweeney, but got three
outs for his league-leading 21st save.
Rangers 13, Mariners 3:
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro had three hits and Royce Clayton had three RBIs
as both homered in Texas' fourth victory in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers (8-5) won his fifth consecutive decision. John
Halama (7-4) gave up five runs in three-plus innings for visiting
Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
