<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Rocker could only watch as the Atlanta Braves' bullpen blew
it.
</P>
<P>
   While Rocker nursed a bleeding callus on his left thumb, the New
York Mets picked on relievers Don Wengert, Kerry Ligtenberg and
Terry Mulholland for a 10-run eighth inning and an improbable 11-8
win Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really let the team down,'' Rocker said. ''Situations like
tonight are the times that I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker split open the callus on his first warmup toss in the
seventh. Fans at Shea Stadium who had been chanting ''We want
Rocker!'' were soon going crazy after Mike Piazza's three-run,
laser-like homer capped the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's no news that we have trouble beating the Braves,'' Piazza
said. ''We come in tight, we press, we kick the ball around.
Hopefully, this will kind of relax us.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza recorded an RBI in his 13th straight game, four short of
the major league mark. The Mets tied a team record for their
biggest inning ever and posted the second-largest comeback in club
history.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never seen anything like that in my life,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   In other NL games, Chicago beat Milwaukee 7-4 in 15 innings, Los
Angeles downed San Francisco 9-2, St. Louis defeated Houston 5-4,
Cincinnati beat Arizona 5-4, Colorado topped San Diego 5-4, Florida
beat Montreal 5-4 and Pittsburgh defeated Philadelphia 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta had its biggest collapse since May 9, 1992, when it blew
a nine-run lead at St. Louis and lost 12-11.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves went 13-15 in June, their first losing month since
September 1996. Third baseman Chipper Jones missed the game to
return to Atlanta, where doctors planned to induce labor in his
wife, Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   The threatened ''Battery Night'' demonstration against Rocker
never took place. In fact, he signed autographs before the game for
the same fans he disparaged last year.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan hit a three-run homer off Eric Cammack in the
eighth, giving Atlanta an 8-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza singled in the bottom half and Robin Ventura's RBI
grounder drove in Derek Bell, who set a Mets record by scoring for
the 10th straight game.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, New York scored nine more runs, with Piazza's
shot to left field coming off Mulholland.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst pitch I've ever thrown,'' Mulholland said.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare official scoring decision, the win was credited to
reliever Armando Benitez, who was still in the bullpen when the
Mets erupted in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez entered in the ninth and got the last three outs.
Cammack was in position to pick up his first major league victory,
but was denied when it was ruled his one-inning, three-run
performance did not warrant it.
</P>
<P>
Cubs 7, Brewers 4
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young drew his team record-tying fifth walk, forcing home
the go-ahead run in the 15th inning, and Sammy Sosa added a two-run
double as Chicago won at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee blew a two-run lead in the ninth. In the Cubs 15th,
pitcher Jon Lieber walked in his first career pinch-hitting
appearance, and Young followed by drawing a walk from rookie Allen
Levrault.
</P>
<P>
Cardinals 5, Astros 4
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire set the record for career home runs at Busch
Stadium as St. Louis beat Houston.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's major league-leading 29th homer this season was the
551st of his career. It also was his 104th in only 215 games at
Busch, moving him ahead of the 103 hit by teammate Ray Lankford.
</P>
<P>
   Houston lost its third in a row.
</P>
<P>
Dodgers 9, Giants 2
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield homered twice and drove in four runs, leading
Kevin Brown and Los Angeles over San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Brown improved to 8-1 in 10 career starts against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley became the first opponent to homer into McCovey's
Cove, the water just outside Pacific Bell Park. He also doubled
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kent drove in two runs, giving him an NL-leading 78 RBIs,
as the Giants lost their third in a row.
</P>
<P>
Reds 5, Diamondbacks 4
</P>
<P>
   Pete Harnisch, fresh off the disabled list, won for the first
time this season and helped himself with a two-run single.
Cincinnati improved to 7-0 all-time at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch, out for nearly four weeks because of weakness in his
rotator cuff, began the night with an 0-4 record and a 9.95 ERA.
</P>
<P>
Marlins 5, Expos 4
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Vladimir Guerrero's error gave Florida the
go-ahead run in the ninth inning at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Mark Kotsay singled and the ball got past
Guerrero, allowing Luis Castillo to score from first base. It was
Guerrero's sixth error of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero raced home from second base on Chris Widger's infield
single in the eighth as Montreal tied it 4-all.
</P>
<P>
Pirates 8, Phillies 3
</P>
<P>
   Wil Cordero drove in four runs as Pittsburgh rallied late to win
at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero hit a two-run triple in a five-run eighth inning and a
two-run single in the ninth. He also doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia leadoff man Doug Glanville broke an 0-for-20 slump
with a single.
</P>
<P>
Rockies 5, Padres 4
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Astacio earned his first victory in seven starts as
Colorado won at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Bragg singled home the tiebreaking run in the seventh
innings. The Rockies won their third in a row.
</P>
</TEXT>
