<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobster Francesco ''Skyball'' Scibelli dies at 87  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) - Francesco Joseph ''Skyball'' Scibelli,
a western Massachusetts mobster with ties to New York's Genovese
crime family, died Thursday. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Scibelli was called ''The Little Guy'' when out of earshot, but
he had prominent stature in bookmaking and other organized crime in
western New England and throughout the east coast since the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Springfield, Scibelli was a familiar figure in the
city. A restaurant owner, he lived in the city's Sixteen Acres
neighborhood for years, but also spent time in Old Saybrook, Conn.
and traveled frequently to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Federal organized crime investigators identified him as a
lieutenant in New York's Genovese crime family, and said he was
well-known in Hartford, where he oversaw gambling for the local
mafia.
</P>
<P>
   He and partner Andrew Pradella were dubbed ''The Scholar Group''
for their prowess at handicapping professional and college sports.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Teresa's 1967 book ''My Life in the Mafia'' noted
Scibelli keen oddskeeping abilities and said he inspired fear in
those he perceived as his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Frank H. Freedman sent Scibelli to
prison in 1976 for 18 months, and again in 1988 for three years,
for his role in organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Violence hit his immediate family in 1972, when the
bullet-riddled body of his son-in-law, Victor C. DeCaro, was pulled
from the Connecticut River, wrapped in a sleeping and bound with
rope.
</P>
<P>
   Scibelli was not related to the late Springfield State Rep.
Anthony Scibelli.
</P>
<P>
   Francesco Scibelli leaves his wife of 43 years, Alice, two sons,
two daughters, a brother and a sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 1955 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
