<DOCNO> APW20000701.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Complains to UN Over Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel has complained to United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan that Lebanon has not fulfilled its
part of a U.N. resolution outlining an Israeli withdrawal from
south Lebanon, a spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli delegation to the United Nations sent a letter to
Annan complaining that the Lebanese army had not deployed in south
Lebanon since Israel's May 24 withdrawal, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Aviv Shiron said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lebanese authorities are located on Israel's side
of the border in some places, Shiron added.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are parts where it appears that they haven't abided by
the border the United Nations set,'' Shiron said. ''We are
demanding they comply with resolution 425.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel's pull out, Lebanon has also accused Israel of not
complying in full with the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations approval of the withdrawal on June 16 was
held up over Lebanese complaints that Israeli troops were still
located in Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. peacekeeping force later cited minor Israeli violations
such as military patrols on roads in Lebanon and Israeli
machine-gun posts on Lebanese land.
</P>
<P>
   Since the withdrawal, demonstrating Lebanese have frequently
thrown stones across the border at Israeli soldiers who have
occasionally responded with gunfire, injuring some.
</P>
<P>
   But the border area has been relatively quiet since the
pullback.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had feared that the anti-Israeli guerrilla group,
Hezbollah, would resume attacks on Israeli targets after the
withdrawal, which created a political and security vacuum in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government has sent some armed forces and police to
south Lebanon to keep order but has not deployed along the
temporary border set by the United Nations until any agreement in
future negotiations irons out a final border.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is slated to deploy 4,500 peacekeeping troops
in south Lebanon once the disagreement over the alleged violations
of both sides have been cleared up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2016 </TRAILER>
