<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Greets NASCAR Racers, Fans  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ROYSE
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- George W. Bush's race for the
presidency made a brief pit stop in the world of car racing
Saturday night, as he came here to shake hands with NASCAR fans,
racing crews and drivers -- people he said ''work for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of stock car racing is made up of ''very good
Americans,'' the Texas governor said. As he walked around the
garage area, crews took short breaks from getting cars ready for
the Pepsi 400, a night race, to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   ''They not only talk about family values, they live it,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the stop wasn't a campaign event, but a diversion from
the campaign. Bush flew in from his Crawford, Texas, ranch near
Waco to serve as grand marshal, but he went into campaign mode
shortly after arriving in the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   He signed shirts already covered with race car sponsors' logos
and briefly talked fishing with a racing fan who urged him to
protect fresh water lakes for fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was hoping his stop at the race works out better for him
than for his father. The former president was grand marshal while
running unsuccessfully for re-election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor is the third in his family to hold the
ceremonial post at the race. His brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
was the grand marshal while he was running for office in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he didn't want to talk about policy during the stop,
although he was scheduled to meet privately with some supporters
before watching the race in the private box of NASCAR president
Bill France.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not interested in any political speeches in the middle
of the race, and I'm not going to give any,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But he took the opportunity to use the NASCAR backdrop as a
symbol of middle-class American values on the Fourth of July
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are the people that work for a living,'' he said over
the din of country music as he looked around the garage area.
''This is America.''
</P>
<P>
   After greeting fans, Bush sat in on the pre-race driver's
meeting, taking a seat in the front row next to driver Dale
Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the drivers that they were important in a country
''starved for role models.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
