<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old box of bones found in Odd Fellows hall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITEHALL, N.Y. (AP) - How odd.
</P>
<P>
   Digging into a renovation project at the 133-year-old
Independent Order of Odd Fellows building, Nils Lommerin discovered
a 5-foot-long box, topped with a metal plaque that read ''Brother''
and containing a partial set of human bones.
</P>
<P>
   The bones - a skull, ribs, and various arm and leg bones - were
discovered by a carpet layer under a trap door in the order's
meeting room, in a spot where the floor had been framed to fit the
miniature casket.
</P>
<P>
   Work on that floor of the building was apparently last done in
1899, said Lommerin's fiancee, Marlo Jones, leading the pair to
speculate the bones had been there for more than a century. The
Whitehall Odd Fellows chapter stopped meeting in the 1960s in the
building that is on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive organization - which dates to 18th century England
and early 19th century America - still has active chapters around
the country, particularly in the Midwest and New England.
</P>
<P>
   The state police Bureau of Criminal Investigation will perform a
forensic exam to see if foul play was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Lommerin and Jones told the Post-Star of Glens Falls they would
like the bones back after the investigation, arguing they are part
of the building's charm.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to put them right back where they were,'' Jones said.
''This has always been his burial place. This is where he
belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitehall is 65 miles north of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 2057 </TRAILER>
