<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexican Ruling Party Faces Accusations
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- On the eve of a tight presidential race, observers and
opposition activists today stepped up accusations against Mexico's ruling party
-- charging it with using the power of the state to illegally influence voting.
The allegations involved scattered incidents, small amounts of money or claims
of pressure on government employees or aid recipients. Officials of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, dismissed most of the reports as
misunderstandings or the result of newspapers' desperation for stories in the
three-day period before the election, when candidates are banned from
campaigning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Terrace Collapses in Lake Erie, Two Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS ISLAND, Ohio (AP) -- Two people have been killed and at least
another 80 injured after a terrace at an island winery in Lake Erie collapsed
this afternoon. The terrace collapsed at the Lonz Winery on an island about 5
miles off the mainland. A dispatcher at the police department in nearby Port
Clinton said the collapse occurred about 5 p.m. Emergency personnel were called
in from as far away as Toledo, Cleveland and Bowling Green. The Coast Guard said
a 47-foot motor lifeboat was at the scene and two more rescue boats were
dispatched.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Complains to U.N. About Lebanon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel has complained to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
that Lebanon has not fulfilled its part of a U.N. resolution outlining an
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, a spokesman said Saturday. The Israeli
delegation to the United Nations sent a letter to Annan complaining that the
Lebanese army had not deployed in south Lebanon since Israel's May 24
withdrawal, Foreign Ministry spokesman Aviv Shiron said. In addition, Lebanese
authorities are located on Israel's side of the border in some places, Shiron
added.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Taken Down in S.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- After decades of debate and mounting pressure from an
NAACP boycott, South Carolina removed the Confederate flag from atop its
Statehouse today in a somber ceremony that paid tribute to its Civil War roots.
The flag, seen as a reminder of slavery for some and a tribute to Southern
heritage for others, flew atop the dome for 38 years. But protests over the flag
continued even as it was being lowered: Civil War re-enactors raised another
Confederate flag on Statehouse grounds, in front of a Confederate soldier's
monument. The new location was part of the compromise reached by the Legislature
in May.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Soldiers Stop Escorting Serbs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- American peacekeepers imposed punitive measures
on a Serb community in Kosovo where riots erupted last month, NATO-led
peacekeepers said Saturday. Until the local community improves cooperation with
the peacekeepers, U.S. soldiers will stop providing armed escorts for Serbs
traveling in convoys to buy food, the U.S. peacekeepers said. All community
improvement projects will also be halted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury Awards $3.3M in Botched Surgery
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A jury has awarded $3.3 million to a man whose doctor
fused the wrong vertebrae in his neck during surgery. Sean E. O'Reilly had a
herniated disk that was supposed to be replaced by bone from his hip. Instead, a
healthy disk below it was removed, witnesses testified. Attorneys for
neurosurgeon William O. DeWeese argued O'Reilly had a congenital disk problem
that resulted in his disks being miscounted, according to O'Reilly's attorney,
Steve Yerrid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Actor Walter Matthau Dies at 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Walter Matthau, the foghorn-voiced master of
crotchety comedy who won an Oscar for ''The Fortune Cookie'' and cemented his
stardom as the sloppy Oscar Madison in ''The Odd Couple,'' died early today of a
heart attack. He was 79. Matthau was pronounced dead at 1:42 a.m. at St. John's
Health Center in Santa Monica, said hospital spokeswoman Lindi Funston.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Armstrong Second in Tour's Time Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France (AP) -- Lance Armstrong got off to a good start in
defense of his Tour de France title with a second-place finish Saturday in the
opening time trial. Britain's David Millar was the winner of the stage, a
10.3-mile sprint. He was timed in 19 minutes, 3 seconds, just 2 seconds faster
than the American in a race against the clock around a futuristic theme park in
western France. Armstrong temporarily relinquished his yellow jersey, but
finished well ahead of Germany's Jan Ullrich, Switzerland's Alex Zulle and
Italy's Marco Pantani, all considered possible threats to his title.
</P>
