<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Board Announces Start of Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TOOTHAKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS,Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's National Election Council
announced Saturday the start of the official election campaign and
called on candidates to respect the nation's electoral law.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo Pizani, a member of the Election Council, urged
candidates to conform to campaign rules because it is impossible to
sanction violators.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only way in which the laws and the regulations are
observed is if the candidates behave like good citizens,'' Pizani
said.
</P>
<P>
   The election has ignited passions and pitted two former coup
leaders against each other in the race for president of this
oil-rich yet poverty-stricken nation of 23 million.
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Chavez, who leads recent polls, is competing
against Francisco Arias Cardenas, a former brother-in-arms who
helped him lead a failed 1992 coup attempt and later turned against
him for abandoning their revolutionary ideals.
</P>
<P>
   Arias held a rally Thursday in downtown Caracas to denounce a
decision to break up an election -- originally slated for May 28 --
that would have encompassed every public office in the country.
Computer problems in the balloting system delayed the election.
</P>
<P>
   Worries that a single vote might overwhelm ballot counters and
confuse voters led the nation's interim legislature last week to
split the postponed elections and rescheduled them for two separate
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential, gubernatorial, congressional, and regional
elections will be July 30; town council elections were rescheduled
for Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The elections are central to President Chavez's efforts to
remake the Venezuelan government and ''re-legitimize'' every public
office as required by a new constitution that the popular head of
state pushed through last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
