<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Seeks Quick Return from DL  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken expects to his latest trip to the
disabled list to be a short one. He's not nearly as sure about his
status for the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken was placed on the 15-day disabled list Wednesday with
pain in his lower back. It was the third time in two seasons that
the Baltimore Orioles' third baseman was sidelined with a back
injury.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that Ripken might be considering
retirement after his latest bout with back problems, but the future
Hall of Famer laid that rumor to rest Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''My big goal is to be ready when the 15 days are up,'' said
Ripken, who watched the Orioles play Toronto from the press box.
''Hopefully I'll heal up and be good as new after 15 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken is scheduled to come off the disabled list on July 13,
but the All-Star game will be held two days earlier in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials have said Ripken could play in his 18th
straight All-Star game if he's elected by the fans and if he and
the Orioles want it to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''First and foremost, my health and how I feel is the most
important thing,'' he said. ''Sitting here right now two days after
the (cortisone) shot and being in pretty good pain, I can't really
consider that as an option. But I would imagine that, knock on
wood, in a week's time if I start to feel good and the pain is gone
and I'm able to resume some sort of activities ... I don't think it
would be too far-fetched if I was totally fine. But it wouldn't be
worth the risk if I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken set a major league record by playing in 2,632 games
before voluntarily ending the streak in September 1998. Last season
was the most difficult of his career, as he twice went on the
disabled list with back problems before undergoing surgery Sept. 23
to decompress nerve root irritation in his back.
</P>
<P>
   He was given periodic rest this season, but hurt himself running
out a grounder Tuesday night in Boston and was placed on the
disabled list the following day.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the same problem I've been dealing with for a while, a
very agitated nerve that runs down my leg. The treatment is to let
the medicine from the shot decrease the inflammation, rest and
spend as little time on my feet as I can the next seven to 10
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching his teammates play never gets any easier for the man
who supplanted Lou Gehrig as baseball's Iron Man.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year I got a feel of what it's like to be away from the
playing field. To sit there and watch the game, it's frustrating,''
he said. ''It seems like you're left out, not doing what you want
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He entered this season on the brink of getting his 3,000th hit,
a feat that occurred on April 15 in Minnesota. But reaching that
milestone was merely a secondary objective for the 39-year-old
Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going into the season, quietly my biggest goal was not going
on the disabled list again,'' he said. ''As luck would have it, I
didn't quite make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
