<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Still No Sign of Indonesian Ferry  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANADO, Indonesia (AP) -- With no trace of their loved ones,
anxious relatives could only cling to rumors Saturday about the
fate of a ferry missing with almost 500 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   After three days, a customs boat mistakenly reported locating
the wooden-hulled vessel off an islet north of the port of Manado,
on Indonesia's Sulawesi Island, taking the families on an emotional
rollercoaster.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spotted a ship from the air, but it wasn't the missing
ferry,'' said Cmdr. Djoko Sudaryono, head of the search-and-rescue
operation, after returning from a reconnaissance flight.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers were checking other unconfirmed sightings and claims,
including one from Christian clergymen that Muslim extremists had
hijacked the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything is possible. We are still looking,'' Sudaryono said.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping disasters with large losses of life are common in
Indonesia, a nation of some 17,000 islands. Captains often overload
their poorly maintained vessels to maximize profits.
</P>
<P>
   As time passes and hopes of finding survivors fade, the search
has assumed an increasingly tense and desperate tone.
</P>
<P>
   A final air and search effort got under way Sunday. If nothing
is found, the search will be called off, Sudaryono said.
</P>
<P>
   Contact with the Cahaya Bahari was lost Thursday soon after its
captain radioed that it was taking on water in stormy seas 1,440
miles northeast of Indonesia's capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry was on a 200-mile voyage to Manado from the Maluku
Islands, a corner of the Indonesian archipelago where violence
between Muslims and Christians has killed almost 3,000 people of
both faiths in the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Local maritime officials reported that the ferry was overloaded
with almost twice the number of passengers it was licensed to
carry. They presumed it went down soon after the distress call.
</P>
<P>
   But rescuers were puzzled that they have found no debris or
other signs of a sinking.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about what happened was rife among scores of tearful
relatives who waited for news at Manado's rundown docks.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are rumors everywhere. Some say the ferry was hijacked
back to the Malukus and that the passengers taken hostage by
Muslims,'' said Yudi Harnoya, whose wife was aboard. ''Others say
it sank straight to the bottom of the ocean. Then there are those
who say survivors are floating in the sea. This makes our situation
very tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudaryono said Sunday's search would move farther east and
closer to the Malukus, including around the island of Doi, where
one unconfirmed sighting was reported.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's cash-strapped navy until now has been able to
dedicate only one aircraft to the operation. However, Sudaryono
said a total of four navy planes would be used along with four
warships and a flotilla of volunteer civilian craft Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2136 </TRAILER>
