<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Find Cocaine on Freighter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- U.S. and Dutch authorities seized
3,080 pounds of cocaine on a Panamanian freighter bound for Spain,
the U.S. Coast Guard said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The cocaine -- with a U.S. street value of more than $100 million
-- was the third major shipment bound for Spain seized in the last
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The cocaine was found on the MV Tiger, a 318-foot freighter
stopped Thursday by a Dutch Navy vessel 200 miles north of
Venezuela, the Coast Guard said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch vessel was on a routine patrol near Dutch Caribbean
territories.
</P>
<P>
   The freighter was carrying fish meal from Balboa, Panama, to
Marin, a port town in Galicia, Spain. The Galician coastline has
become a common entry point for South American and North African
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said U.S. Coast Guard officials aboard the Dutch
vessel became suspicious when they spotted streaks and scratches on
the freighter's aft section. Such marks can be left when cargo is
pulled on board while at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities boarded the ship and found 50 bales full of cocaine,
the Coast Guard said. The Panamanian government gave permission to
seize the vessel and detain the crew of 10 Ukrainians, three
Peruvians and a Venezuelan.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, Spanish Civil Guards with help from the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Agency stopped a freighter near Martinique and found
more than two tons of cocaine bound for Galicia. Twenty-one people
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Spanish authorities found 440 pounds of cocaine on a
Panamanian-registered ship in southern port of Algeciras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2212 </TRAILER>
