<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
1 Dead, Several Injured in Terrace Collapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS ISLAND, Ohio (AP) -- A cement terrace loaded with tourists
collapsed at an island winery in Lake Erie today, killing one person and
injuring dozens, authorities said. Coast Guard officials had earlier said that
two people were killed in the accident. The collapse left a gaping hole in the
floor of the lakefront terrace at Lonz Winery's century-old main building, a
fortresslike mansion on the National Register of Historic Places. ''The whole
deck just disappeared, it just fell,'' Barbara Kraft, visiting the island from
Rochester Hills, Mich., told WBNS-TV in Columbus. Paramedics estimated 30 people
were critically injured.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Holiday Travelers Brave Gas Prices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Midwesterners gassed up their vehicles and hit the road for
the holiday weekend, as high gas prices -- which led two states to suspend their
gas sales tax and prompted a federal investigation into possible price gouging
-- continued to fall. ''It's the Fourth of July weekend. What are you going to
do -- stay home? Plans are all on,'' said Tom Woody of Madison, Wisc., as he
filled up his tank en route to a paddling trip in southern Wisconsin. Illinois
pump prices took a big dip today -- with Chicago prices falling below $2 a
gallon for the first time since Memorial Day -- as station owners began passing
along savings created by the state's lifting of a 5 percent sales tax on
gasoline.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Outcome Uncertain in Mexico Elections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAUCALPAN, Mexico (AP) -- On the eve of elections, the National Action
Party's Vicente Fox is running roughly even in the polls with Francisco
Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which hasn't lost a
presidential race since it was created as a party of power in 1929. For perhaps
the first time in a century, and perhaps the first time ever, Mexicans are
voting with a great uncertainty about who their next president will be. The PRI,
which once won elections with 80 to 90 percent of the claimed vote, is
struggling to surpass 42 percent this year against the five other candidates on
the ballot.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton's Defense: Just a Normal Guy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton's privilege to practice law in
his home state may hinge on how well his lawyers make a case for treating the
country's chief executive like anyone else. A committee of the Arkansas Supreme
Court filed suit yesterday seeking Clinton's disbarment, saying he gave
misleading testimony under oath about his relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. The lawsuit followed a May 19 vote by the state Supreme
Court Committee on Professional Conduct to strip Clinton of his law license for
violating procedures governing attorneys' ethical behavior.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Still No Sign of Indonesian Ferry
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANADO, Indonesia (AP) -- With no trace of their loved ones, anxious
relatives could only cling to rumors Saturday about the fate of a ferry missing
with almost 500 people aboard. After three days, a customs boat mistakenly
reported locating the wooden-hulled vessel off an islet north of the port of
Manado, on Indonesia's Sulawesi Island, taking the families on an emotional
rollercoaster. ''We spotted a ship from the air, but it wasn't the missing
ferry,'' said Cmdr. Djoko Sudaryono, head of the search-and-rescue operation,
after returning from a reconnaissance flight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Takes Down Confederate Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- After decades of debate and mounting pressure from an
NAACP boycott, South Carolina removed the Confederate flag from atop its
Statehouse today in a somber ceremony that paid tribute to its Civil War roots.
The flag, seen as a reminder of slavery for some and a tribute to Southern
heritage for others, flew atop the dome for 38 years. But protests over the flag
continued even as it was being lowered.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro Warns Next U.S. President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANZANILLO, Cuba (AP) -- Fidel Castro defiantly warned the next U.S.
president today not to try to defeat his socialist revolution, as the Cuban
government launched a new series of mass demonstrations after Elian Gonzalez's
return. ''Whoever may be the new president of the United States should know that
Cuba is and will be here with its ideas, its example, and the unbendable
rebellion of its people,'' Castro wrote in a letter read before hundreds of
thousands of people gathered to protest U.S. policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mac Homers, Cards Beat Astros 10-9
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire hit his major league-leading 30th home run and
Fernando Tatis homered for the first time since coming off the disabled list as
the St. Louis Cardinals beat the Houston Astros 10-9 today. McGwire hit the
first pitch he saw from Octavio Dotel for a three-run shot in the first inning.
He reached the 30-homer mark for the 11th time in his career.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
