<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crear Wins 110-Meter Hurdles  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- As soon as he crossed the finish line,
Mark Crear felt the exhilaration of triumph -- and then quickly felt
the pain in his bloody right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Crear won the 110-meter hurdles Saturday in 13.20 seconds, the
fastest mark by an American this year. It was only one-hundredth of
a second off the world's fastest this year, a mark of 13.19 by
Cuba's Anier Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Crear held off Dawane Wallace (13.26) and Chris Phillips (13.27)
despite getting spiked during the race. He finished the event with
blood on the fourth finger and pinkie of his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''Long-distance runners get spiked in the legs, we get spiked in
the fingers. I may have even spiked myself,'' Crear said. ''But
when you win, it makes the pain go away a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The meet, formally called the GMC Envoy Track &AMP; Field Open and
held at Stanford University, was used by many competitors as a
warmup for the U.S. Olympic trials to be held at Sacramento in
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Most top American track and field performers were not at the
meet, which was the third leg of USA Track &AMP; Field's three-meet
outdoor Golden Spike Tour. Instead, they were in Europe at meets
offering far more money and prestige.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Crear rushed off after his victory to his home in
Vallencia in southern California to pack for a trip Sunday to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going back home, kiss my daughter and then take off for
Switzerland,'' said Crear, the 1996 Olympic silver medalist and the
top-ranked 110 hurdler in the world in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other top performances at the meet were Adam Nelson's
winning mark of 71 feet, 2&AMP;frac12; inches on his final attempt in the shot
put, the third-longest toss in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Dragila won the women's pole vault by clearing 14-10&AMP;frac14;.
Kellie Suttle cleared the same height for her career best, but
Dragila won because she had fewer misses. Both women failed in
three attempts at 15-2&AMP;frac14;, which would have been a world record.
</P>
<P>
   John Capel won the men's 100 in 10.14 and Carlette Guidry won
the women's 100 in 11.06.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2304 </TRAILER>
