<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amateur historians say Thomas Jefferson kin buried in Orange County </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TUXEDO, N.Y. (AP) - A pair of local historians claim to have
found the grave of an illegitimate son of founding father Thomas
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   But at a press conference Saturday to discuss their findings,
one of the amateur sleuths disappeared on the way to the headstone
belonging to a man named Thomas Jefferson. Reporters were left to
speculate if they were indeed standing before the final resting
spot of the son of a president and his slave mistress, Sally
Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, Roger King, has been restoring tombstones in
Orange County for three decades, according to the Times
Herald-Record of Middletown. He told the gathered media he had
found a broken stone lying near Thomas Jefferson's headstone that
read: ''Son of Thomas Jefferson and Sally Heming (sic).''
</P>
<P>
   King said he discovered the worn gravestone last summer near a
stone that read: ''In memory of Thomas Jefferson who died April 25,
1855 Ae 46 Yrs &AMP; 12 Ds.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the space of 1,000 feet between the gravesite and the
diner where Saturday's press conference was conducted, King
vanished. Reporters tried unsuccessfully to track him down.
</P>
<P>
   This illegitimate son is believed to have been born in 1809, the
result of a love affair between the third president of the United
States and his slave mistress, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   King's gravestone find supplemented research done by Robert
Brennan, a retired history and math teacher, who has been
conducting genealogical research into the Jeffersons of Orange
County.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS documentary earlier this year revealed DNA evidence that
proved Jefferson had at least one child with Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuxedo is 35 miles north of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 2308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-NBC White House Reporter Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ray Scherer, a former chief White House
correspondent for NBC News and RCA Corp., executive, died Saturday
of cancer at his home in Washington. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Scherer joined the network as a news writer in 1947 after
working as a newspaper feature writer in his native Fort Wayne,
Ind., and quickly became an on-air reporter. A pioneer television
journalist, he was among the first to report live from the White
House and from the floor of the presidential nominating
conventions, in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   He served as NBC's London correspondent from 1969 to 1973 and
returned to Washington as a senior reporter until becoming vice
president of RCA's Washington office in 1975. He retired in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Scherer leaves his wife of 49 years, Barbara, two children and
two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
