<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 80-year-old killed by fire truck  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - An 80-year-old woman died Saturday after being
hit by a fire truck that was racing to a blaze near the
Williamsburg Bridge, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Ngor Tong Shiu, was hit at 11:52 a.m. just around the
corner from her home. She was pronounced dead at a hospital at
about 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred at Rutgers and Madison streets in
Manhattan as the truck was responding to a confirmed fire at 52
Rutgers Street. The woman lived on Madison.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, in a 16-story building, was under control by 12:33
p.m. No injuries were reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-01-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000701.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Monuments Are Vulnerable  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A study commissioned by the National Park
Service concludes that Washington's monuments are vulnerable to
terrorist attack and that the service needs a budget boost to
counter the threat, The Washington Post reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Post, saying it had obtained a copy of the report, said in
Sunday editions that the 200-page document makes a direct
correlation between the vulnerability of things like the Lincoln
Memorial and Washington Monument and funding for the U.S. Park
Police, the law enforcement arm of the park service.
</P>
<P>
   ''As symbols of America's heritage, they are high-profile
landmarks, not well protected, popular, attract many visitors daily
and require open and easy accessibility,'' says the report.
</P>
<P>
   It said an additional one-time expenditure of $3 million would
bring eight of the most popular monuments up to security standards.
</P>
<P>
   It also says many shortcomings involved a lack of manpower and
poor communication equipment assigned to Park Police.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Langston, head of Park Police, told the Post that while
protection of other government buildings in the city has increased,
that has not happened with the monuments and memorials guarded by
the Park Police.
</P>
<P>
   However, Park Police Sgt. Rob MacLean told the paper there was
no reason for people to be concerned about gathering for things
like the Fourth of July fireworks celebration on the Mall because
virtually every officer on the force is on duty for events like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've taken steps to ensure safety measures are in place to
take care of any situation that may occur,'' said MacLean.
</P>
<P>
   The Post pointed out that, while neither agency would comment on
Park Police readiness, both the FBI and the U.S. Secret Service
share responsibility for protecting against terrorist acts that
might be directed against any government installation.
</P>
<P>
   And Bruce Hoffman, a Washington-based counterterrorism expert
for Rand Corp., a nonprofit public policy institute, said it is a
given that government monuments are potential targets.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are by very definition national monuments, which means
they're there for the public,'' Hoffman told the Post. ''So no one
can look at them and say they're not vulnerable. Of course they're
vulnerable. But everything is vulnerable. It comes to a point where
you have to accept that we can't have a risk-free society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2330 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
