<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stars' Carbonneau To Retire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Dallas Stars center Guy Carbonneau, a three-time
Selke Trophy winner who won three Stanley Cups, announced his
retirement Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau was a gritty player who made his mark in 19 seasons
as a defensive center. He won the NHL's Selke Trophy, given to the
league's best defensive forward, in consecutive years from 1988-89
and again in 1992 with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau spent the last five seasons with Dallas, winning the
Stanley Cup with the Stars in 1999. He spent 13 seasons playing for
the Canadiens, who won the Cup in 1986 and 1993. He also played 42
games for St. Louis in the lockout-shortened 1994-95 season.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau had 260 goals and 403 assists in 1,318 regular-season
games, and 38 goals and 55 assists in 231 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   At 40, Carbonneau was the league's oldest player last season. He
wound up having one of his best seasons in recent years, helping
Dallas earn a return trip to the Stanley Cup finals. Carbonneau had
10 goals and six assists in 69 regular-season games, and two goals
and four assists in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A front-office or coaching position could be next for
Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Canadiens general manager Rejean Houle asked
Stars counterpart Bob Gainey for permission to have discussions
with Carbonneau. Jacques Lemaire, the Canadiens' senior consultant
to the general manager last season, left to coach the expansion
Minnesota Wild.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am in retirement,'' Carbonneau said. ''I will certainly meet
with the heads of the Canadiens and see what they have to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked with Bob Gainey before leaving Dallas. They haven't
specified what job they'd like me to do. But I'll weigh the pros
and cons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2335 </TRAILER>
