<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Army To Appoint New Government  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Defying rebels who took over Fiji's parliament
and demanded that ethnic Indians be stripped of political power,
the army said Sunday it would appoint a temporary government next
week that would include Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement appeared to raise the stakes in a political
standoff that began May 19, when the rebels stormed the Indian-led
parliament of this South Pacific island nation in what they called
a battle for the trampled rights of indigenous Fijians. They
continue to hold 27 members of parliament hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be ethnic Indo-Fijians in the interim government
lineup, although percentages I cannot say at this point in time,''
Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   The military -- which assumed power 10 days after the raid on
parliament -- said last week that it would appoint an interim
government without input from the hostage takers, who had been
demanding a role in the naming process.
</P>
<P>
   Tarakinikini said Thursday that the temporary government would
take office only once the hostages were released. But on Sunday he
said the army will not wait.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the military's latest statement, rebel spokesman
Jo Nata said ''we hope they are prepared for the implications of
their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not elaborate, but rebel leader George Speight has said
in recent days that any military action perceived as
anti-indigenous could result in violence by his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Talks to free the hostages broke down last week over what the
army said was an 11th hour demand by Speight's group that they be
allowed to name a new president.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Tarakinikini said the army was ''determined to
resolve the crisis in a peaceful manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to maintain that the door for negotiations is
still open,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rebels' demands to disenfranchise Fiji's Indians
have already been met, including the firing of Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry -- a hostage -- and the elimination of the
country's 1997 multiracial constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Tarakinikini appeared to leave open the possibility that the
interim government, which he said would be named by Thursday, could
resurrect that constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The review of the constitution will be left to the interim
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's position is that there be no Indians in the interim
government.
</P>
<P>
   Indians were first brought to Fiji over a century ago by English
colonialists seeking indentured laborers in the country's rich
sugarcane fields. They make up about 44 percent of Fiji's
population, while indigenous Fijians account for about 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, a group of indigenous Fijian youths staged a day of
fasting and prayer in the capital, Suva, in an effort to heal the
ethnic wounds that prompted the crisis. They hugged and shook hands
with ethnic Indians and called for greater tolerance on Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's surround our Indian brothers and sisters with our
Christian love,'' group leader Mika Yasa Mudreilagi said as people
hugged and sobbed. ''Please forgive us for any hurt that we have
caused you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-01-00 2348 </TRAILER>
