<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, July 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Army To Appoint New Government
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Defying rebels who took over Fiji's parliament and
demanded that ethnic Indians be stripped of political power, the army said
Sunday it would appoint a temporary government next week that would include
Indians. The announcement appeared to raise the stakes in a political standoff
that began May 19, when the rebels stormed the Indian-led parliament of this
South Pacific island nation in what they called a battle for the trampled rights
of indigenous Fijians. They continue to hold 27 members of parliament hostage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Terrace Collapses, Leaving 2 Dead in Ohio
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS ISLAND, Ohio (AP) -- Two people are dead and dozens injured after
a cement terrace loaded with tourists collapsed at an island winery in Lake Erie
Saturday, authorities said. The collapse left a gaping hole in the floor of the
lakefront terrace at Lonz Winery's century-old main building, a fortresslike
mansion on the National Register of Historic Places. ''The whole deck just
disappeared, it just fell,'' Barbara Kraft, visiting the island from Rochester
Hills, Mich., told WBNS-TV in Columbus. Paramedics estimated 30 people were
critically injured.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Board Announces Start of Campaign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARACAS,Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's National Election Council announced
Saturday the start of the official election campaign and called on candidates to
respect the nation's electoral law. Leonardo Pizani, a member of the Election
Council, urged candidates to conform to campaign rules because it is impossible
to sanction violators.President Hugo Chavez, who leads recent polls, is
competing against Francisco Arias Cardenas, a former brother-in-arms who helped
him lead a failed 1992 coup attempt and later turned against him for abandoning
their revolutionary ideals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
$100M in Cocaine Seized in Caribbean
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- U.S. and Dutch authorities seized 3,080 pounds
of cocaine on a Panamanian freighter bound for Spain, the U.S. Coast Guard said
Saturday. The cocaine -- with a U.S. street value of more than $100 million --
was the third major shipment bound for Spain seized in the last two weeks. The
cocaine was found on the MV Tiger, a 318-foot freighter stopped Thursday by a
Dutch Navy vessel 200 miles north of Venezuela, the Coast Guard said in a
written statement. The Dutch vessel was on a routine patrol near Dutch Caribbean
territories.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Wash. Monuments Vulnerable
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A study commissioned by the National Park Service
concludes that Washington's monuments are vulnerable to terrorist attack and
that the service needs a budget boost to counter the threat, The Washington Post
reported. The Post, saying it had obtained a copy of the report, said in Sunday
editions that the 200-page document makes a direct correlation between the
vulnerability of things like the Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument and
funding for the U.S. Park Police, the law enforcement arm of the park service.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombia Missile Attack Kills One
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CALI, Colombia (AP) -- Assailants launched crude missiles outside police
headquarters in Colombia's third-largest city Saturday, killing one passer-by
and wounding at least 11 others. No one immediately claimed responsibility for
the attack, which was similar to ones previously carried out by the country's
main rebel group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. Four
explosive devices were launched from the back of a pickup truck parked next to
the police headquarters in downtown Cali. One landed on a car passing by on the
street, exploded and killed the driver.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro: U.S. Won't Break Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANZANILLO, Cuba (AP) -- Fidel Castro defiantly warned the next U.S.
president Saturday not to try to defeat his socialist revolution, as the Cuban
government launched a new series of mass demonstrations after Elian Gonzalez's
return. ''Whoever may be the new president of the United States should know that
Cuba is and will be here with its ideas, its example, and the unbendable
rebellion of its people,'' Castro wrote in a letter read before hundreds of
thousands of people gathered to protest U.S. policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tigers Beat Royals 8-7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Rob Fick's RBI single tied it in the ninth, then
Ricky Bottalico walked Rich Becker with the bases loaded to force in the winning
run as the Detroit Tigers outlasted the Kansas City Royals 8-7 Saturday night.
Bottalico (7-2) gave up singles to Tony Clark and Dean Palmer starting the ninth
as he blew his sixth save in 11 opportunities despite the Tigers' stranding 16
runners.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
